hree [[poplars]].<ref>[http://somogy.hu/publikaciok/kiraly-lajos-somogyi-helysegnevek-nepi-es.html Lajos Kir\u00e1ly : Somogyi helys\u00e9gnevek n\u00e9pi \u00e9s ...]</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.terkepcentrum.hu/index.asp?go=map&tid=8837 Street map (Hungarian)]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Somogy-geo-stub}}\n\n{{Nagyat\u00e1d District}}\n{{Somogy}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haromfa}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Somogy County]]\n[[Category:Hungarian German communities in Somogy County]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Slovene communities in Somogy County]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H%C3%A1romfa"}
{"title_page": "H\u00e1cs", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n| official_name          = H\u00e1cs\n| settlement_type        = Village\n| image_skyline          = H\u00e1cs 4.jpg\n| image_caption          = Agricultural plant in H\u00e1cs\n| image_shield           = HUN H\u00e1cs COA.jpg\n| timezone               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset             = +1\n| timezone_DST           = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST         = +2\n| map                    = [[Image:SomogyMegye.png|center|thumb|275px|Location of Somogy county in Hungary]]\n| subdivision_type       = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n| subdivision_name       = {{HUN}}\n| subdivision_type1      = [[Regions of Hungary|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1      = [[Southern Transdanubia]]\n| subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Hungary|County]]\n| subdivision_name2      = [[Somogy County|Somogy]]\n| subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Hungary|District]]\n| subdivision_name3      = [[Fony\u00f3d District|Fony\u00f3d]]\n| subdivision_type4      = [[List of Catholic dioceses in Hungary|RC Diocese]]\n| subdivision_name4      = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Kaposv\u00e1r|Kaposv\u00e1r]]\n| area_total_km2         = 21.28\n| population_total       = 360<ref>[http://www.ksh.hu/apps/hntr.telepules?p_lang=EN&p_id=18634 H\u00e1cs, KSH]</ref>\n| population_as_of       = 2017\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| population_demonym     = h\u00e1csi\n| postal_code_type       = [[Postal code]]\n| postal_code            = 8694\n| area_code              = (+36) 85\n| blank4_name_sec1       = [[NUTS statistical regions of Hungary|NUTS 3 code]]\n| blank4_info_sec1       = HU232\n| blank5_name_sec2       = [[List of members of the National Assembly of Hungary (2018\u201322)|MP]]\n| blank5_info_sec2       = [[J\u00f3zsef Attila M\u00f3ring]] ([[KDNP]])\n| pushpin_map            = Hungary \n| pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of H\u00e1cs\n| pushpin_mapsize        = \n| coordinates            = {{coord|46.64961|17.68701|region:HU|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''H\u00e1cs''' is a village in [[Somogy County|Somogy]] county, [[Hungary]].\n\n==Geography==\nIt lies 14&nbsp;km southern of [[Fony\u00f3d]] and 6&nbsp;km southern of [[Lengyelt\u00f3ti]].\n\nThe settlement consists of three parts, the former H\u00e1cs village and two outer uninhabited territories, ''B\u00e9ndekpuszta'' and ''G\u00e1rdonypuszta''. The village of Putenda (''Petendpuszta'' between 1849 and 1936) was earlier a separate settlement, but it has grown together with H\u00e1cs.\n\n==History==\nH\u00e1cs was first mentioned as ''Alchy'', ''B\u00e9ndekpuszta'' as ''Bennuk'' and ''Terra Bendek'', ''Putenda'' as ''Pettend'', ''G\u00e1rdonypuszta'' as ''Gardon'' in medieval documents. During the ancient times Germanic tribes and Avars settled there. There were also two villages, ''Thuul'' and ''Sutak'' on this territory according to the papal [[tithe]] register. The second also had its own parish. They all disappeared during the [[Ottoman Hungary|Ottoman invasion]].\n\nThe landowners of ''Nagyh\u00e1cs'', the ''Inkey'' family invited Lutheran Germans to ''Nagyh\u00e1cs'' who came from [[Bonyh\u00e1d]] and its surrounding in [[Tolna County (former)|Tolna County]]. Originally they came from [[Hesse]] and [[W\u00fcrttemberg]] to the [[Hungarian Kingdom]]. ''Antal Inkey'' and his wife, ''Ter\u00e9zia Kiss'' made a contract with 30 German settlers which detailed regulated their duties and laws. The first teacher of H\u00e1cs was ''Georgius Ritzl'' who worked there between 1828 and 1858.\n\nThe landowners of ''Kish\u00e1cs'', the ''Lengyel'' family settled Lutheran as well as Roman Catholic Germans from [[Veszpr\u00e9m County (former)|Veszpr\u00e9m]] and [[Tolna County (former)|Tolna County]]. There were also some Hungarian families in the village.\n\nThe landowner of ''Pettend'', ''Ferdin\u00e1nd Fechtig'' settled Lutheran and Roman Catholic Hungarians and Germans in 1849. But according to the records there were also 2-3 Serbian and 1 Jewish family among the settlers.\n\nIn 1849 the whole population of H\u00e1cs was German with 414 people of which 400 Lutherans and 14 Roman Catholics. Four years later, in 1853 41 Lutheran family came to ''Nagyh\u00e1cs''. There was a huge cholera epidemic in 1855 which caused several deaths. In this years the residents built their new Lutheran church and the building of their school. The second one does not exist today. Until 1870 their worships were held only in German, after that in both Hungarian and German respectively on different Sundays.<ref>[https://library.hungaricana.hu/hu/view/SOMM_SomAlm_052/?pg=121&layout=s&query=h\u00e1cs Szita L\u00e1szl\u00f3: Somogy megyei nemzetis\u00e9gek telep\u00fcl\u00e9st\u00f6rt\u00e9nete a XVIII-XIX. sz\u00e1zadban - Somogyi Almanach 52. (Kaposv\u00e1r, 1993)]</ref>\n\n''Zsigmond Inkey'' changed his lands with ''Nepomuk J\u00e1nos Zichy'', therefore became the ''Zichy'' family the owner of H\u00e1cs. There was a huge conflagration in which the half of the houses burnt down. In 1876 the ''Inkey'' family established a foundation to spread the usage of Hungarian language among the residents which helped the [[magyarization]]. The village became administratively independent on August 9, 1907 from [[Lengyelt\u00f3ti]]. Its first judge was ''J\u00e1nos Gy\u00f6rgy Moschberger''. Later he was followed by G\u00e1bor Ember, Henrik Koch, K\u00e1lm\u00e1n F\u0171zfa, S\u00e1ndor Kirner and M\u00e1ty\u00e1s Vogel. In [[Austria-Hungary]] at the turn of the 19th century several people emigrated to the [[United States of America]] because of the poverty and joblessness. Fifty people left H\u00e1cs for the USA, most of them came back. In 1910 a new Lutheran school was built and the old one demolished. There was also a Roman Catholic school between 1878 and 1953.<ref>[https://library.hungaricana.hu/hu/view/SOMM_SomAlm_052/?pg=121&layout=s&query=h\u00e1cs Szita L\u00e1szl\u00f3: Somogy megyei nemzetis\u00e9gek telep\u00fcl\u00e9st\u00f6rt\u00e9nete a XVIII-XIX. sz\u00e1zadban - Somogyi Almanach 52. (Kaposv\u00e1r, 1993)]</ref>\n\nSeveral residents of H\u00e1cs fought in the world wars. In the [[First World War]] died 21, in the [[Second World War]] 31. There are two marble plaques on the churches remembering on those who fell. Between the two world wars the village experienced a great economic development. In 1945 the older land system was abolished and all the residents got smaller land portions. The Catholics built a new church in 1953.\n\nOn October 26, 1956 the residents marched on the streets of the village and declared their solidarity with the revolutionaries of the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]]. They elected their own Revolutionary Committee and a new secretary of the village council.\n\n==Main sights==\n* Lutheran Church - was dedicated on October 18, 1936\n* Roman Catholic Church - was built between 1949 and 1953 in [[Neo-Romanesque]], was dedicated to [[Elizabeth of Hungary|Saint Elisabeth]]\n* medieval chapel ruins in ''B\u00e9ndekpuszta'' - was built in the 12th or 13th century in [[Gothic style]]. In 1590 Turkish troops attacked the village. The inhabitants flew into the chapel. The Turks set the roof on fire, therefore they all died.\n* [[Classicist style|Classicist]] chapel - was built in 1857 on the ruins of the medieval chapel\n* stone cross - was built on the ruins of a 19th century chapel in ''G\u00e1rdonypuszta''\n* fish pond in ''G\u00e1rdonypuszta''\n\n==Gallery==\n<center>\n<gallery widths=\"120\" heights=\"120px\" perrow=\"6\" style=\"border: 5px solid #a86; box-shadow: 0.1em 0.1em 0.5em rgba(0,0,0,0.75); border-radius: 0.5em;\">\nFile:H\u00e1cs 1.jpg\nFile:H\u00e1cs 2.jpg\nFile:H\u00e1cs 3.jpg\nFile:H\u00e1cs 5.jpg\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==Literature==\n* L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Szita : Somogy megyei nemzetis\u00e9gek telep\u00fcl\u00e9st\u00f6rt\u00e9nete a XVIII-XIX. sz\u00e1zadban - Somogyi Almanach 52. (Kaposv\u00e1r, 1993)\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.terkepcentrum.hu/index.asp?go=map&tid=18634 Street map (Hungarian)]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Fony\u00f3d District}}\n{{Somogy}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hacs}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Somogy County]]\n[[Category:Hungarian German communities in Somogy County]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n| official_name          = H\u00e1cs\n| settlement_type        = Village\n| image_skyline          = H\u00e1cs 4.jpg\n| image_caption          = Agricultural plant in H\u00e1cs\n| image_shield           = HUN H\u00e1cs COA.jpg\n| timezone               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset             = +1\n| timezone_DST           = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST         = +2\n| map                    = [[Image:SomogyMegye.png|center|thumb|275px|Location of Somogy county in Hungary]]\n| subdivision_type       = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n| subdivision_name       = {{HUN}}\n| subdivision_type1      = [[Regions of Hungary|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1      = [[Southern Transdanubia]]\n| subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Hungary|County]]\n| subdivision_name2      = [[Somogy County|Somogy]]\n| subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Hungary|District]]\n| subdivision_name3      = [[Fony\u00f3d District|Fony\u00f3d]]\n| subdivision_type4      = [[List of Catholic dioceses in Hungary|RC Diocese]]\n| subdivision_name4      = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Kaposv\u00e1r|Kaposv\u00e1r]]\n| area_total_km2         = 21.28\n| population_total       = 360<ref>[http://www.ksh.hu/apps/hntr.telepules?p_lang=EN&p_id=18634 H\u00e1cs, KSH]</ref>\n| population_as_of       = 2017\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| population_demonym     = h\u00e1csi\n| postal_code_type       = [[Postal code]]\n| postal_code            = 8694\n| area_code              = (+36) 85\n| blank4_name_sec1       = [[NUTS statistical regions of Hungary|NUTS 3 code]]\n| blank4_info_sec1       = HU232\n| blank5_name_sec2       = [[List of members of the National Assembly of Hungary (2018\u201322)|MP]]\n| blank5_info_sec2       = [[J\u00f3zsef Attila M\u00f3ring]] ([[KDNP]])\n| pushpin_map            = Hungary \n| pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of H\u00e1cs\n| pushpin_mapsize        = \n| coordinates            = {{coord|46.64961|17.68701|region:HU|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''H\u00e1cs''' is a village in [[Somogy County|Somogy]] county, [[Hungary]].\n\n==Geography==\nIt lies 14 km southern of [[Fony\u00f3d]] and 6 km southern of [[Lengyelt\u00f3ti]]. \n\nThe settlement consists of three parts, the former H\u00e1cs village and two outer uninhabited territories, ''B\u00e9ndekpuszta'' and ''G\u00e1rdonypuszta''. The village of Putenda (''Petendpuszta'' between 1849 and 1936) was earlier a separate settlement, but it has grown together with H\u00e1cs.\n\n==History==\nH\u00e1cs was first mentioned as ''Alchy'', ''B\u00e9ndekpuszta'' as ''Bennuk'' and ''Terra Bendek'', ''Putenda'' as ''Pettend'', ''G\u00e1rdonypuszta'' as ''Gardon'' in medieval documents. During the ancient times Germanic tribes and Avars settled there. There were also two villages, ''Thuul'' and ''Sutak'' on this territory according to the papal [[tithe]] register. The second also had its own parish. They all disappeared during the [[Ottoman Hungary|Ottoman invasion]].\n\nThe landowners of ''Nagyh\u00e1cs'', the ''Inkey'' family invited Lutheran Germans to ''Nagyh\u00e1cs'' who came from [[Bonyh\u00e1d]] and its surrounding in [[Tolna County (former)|Tolna County]]. Originally they came from [[Hesse]] and [[W\u00fcrttemberg]] to the [[Hungarian Kingdom]]. ''Antal Inkey'' and his wife, ''Ter\u00e9zia Kiss'' made a contract with 30 German settlers which detailed regulated their duties and laws. The first teacher of H\u00e1cs was ''Georgius Ritzl'' who worked there between 1828 and 1858.\n\nThe landowners of ''Kish\u00e1cs'', the ''Lengyel'' family settled Lutheran as well as Roman Catholic Germans from [[Veszpr\u00e9m County (former)|Veszpr\u00e9m]] and [[Tolna County (former)|Tolna County]]. There were also some Hungarian families in the village.\n\nThe landowner of ''Pettend'', ''Ferdin\u00e1nd Fechtig'' settled Lutheran and Roman Catholic Hungarians and Germans in 1849. But according to the records there were also 2-3 Serbian and 1 Jewish family among the settlers.\n\nIn 1849 the whole population of H\u00e1cs was German with 414 people of which 400 Lutherans and 14 Roman Catholics. Four years later, in 1853 41 Lutheran family came to ''Nagyh\u00e1cs''. There was a huge cholera epidemic in 1855 which caused several deaths. In this years the residents built their new Lutheran church and the building of their school. The second one does not exist today. Until 1870 their worships were held only in German, after that in both Hungarian and German respectively on different Sundays.<ref>[https://library.hungaricana.hu/hu/view/SOMM_SomAlm_052/?pg=121&layout=s&query=h\u00e1cs Szita L\u00e1szl\u00f3: Somogy megyei nemzetis\u00e9gek telep\u00fcl\u00e9st\u00f6rt\u00e9nete a XVIII-XIX. sz\u00e1zadban - Somogyi Almanach 52. (Kaposv\u00e1r, 1993)]</ref>\n\n''Zsigmond Inkey'' changed his lands with ''Nepomuk J\u00e1nos Zichy'', therefore became the ''Zichy'' family the owner of H\u00e1cs. There was a huge conflagration in which the half of the houses burnt down. In 1876 the ''Inkey'' family established a foundation to spread the usage of Hungarian language among the residents which helped the [[magyarization]]. The village became administratively independent on August 9, 1907 from [[Lengyelt\u00f3ti]]. Its first judge was ''J\u00e1nos Gy\u00f6rgy Moschberger''. Later he was followed by G\u00e1bor Ember, Henrik Koch, K\u00e1lm\u00e1n F\u0171zfa, S\u00e1ndor Kirner and M\u00e1ty\u00e1s Vogel. In [[Austria-Hungary]] at the turn of the 19th century several people emigrated to the [[United States of America]] because of the poverty and joblessness. Fifty people left H\u00e1cs for the USA, most of them came back. In 1910 a new Lutheran school was built and the old one demolished. There was also a Roman Catholic school between 1878 and 1953. <ref>[https://library.hungaricana.hu/hu/view/SOMM_SomAlm_052/?pg=121&layout=s&query=h\u00e1cs Szita L\u00e1szl\u00f3: Somogy megyei nemzetis\u00e9gek telep\u00fcl\u00e9st\u00f6rt\u00e9nete a XVIII-XIX. sz\u00e1zadban - Somogyi Almanach 52. (Kaposv\u00e1r, 1993)]</ref>\n\nSeveral residents of H\u00e1cs fought in the world wars. In the [[First World War]] died 21, in the [[Second World War]] 31. There are two marble plaques on the churches remembering on those who fell. Between the two world wars the village experienced a great economic development. In 1945 the older land system was abolished and all the residents got smaller land portions. The Catholics built a new church in 1953. \n\nOn October 26, 1956 the residents marched on the streets of the village and declared their solidarity with the revolutionaries of the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]]. They elected their own Revolutionary Committee and a new secretary of the village council.\n\n==Main sights==\n* Lutheran Church - was dedicated on October 18, 1936\n* Roman Catholic Church - was built between 1949 and 1953 in [[Neo-Romanesque]], was dedicated to [[Elizabeth of Hungary|Saint Elisabeth]]\n* medieval chapel ruins in ''B\u00e9ndekpuszta'' - was built in the 12th or 13th century in [[Gothic style]]. In 1590 Turkish troops attacked the village. The inhabitants flew into the chapel. The Turks set the roof on fire, therefore they all died.\n* [[Classicist style|Classicist]] chapel - was built in 1857 on the ruins of the medieval chapel\n* stone cross - was built on the ruins of a 19th century chapel in ''G\u00e1rdonypuszta''\n* fish pond in ''G\u00e1rdonypuszta''\n\n==Gallery==\n<center>\n<gallery widths=\"120\" heights=\"120px\" perrow=\"6\" style=\"border: 5px solid #a86; box-shadow: 0.1em 0.1em 0.5em rgba(0,0,0,0.75); border-radius: 0.5em;\">\nFile:H\u00e1cs 1.jpg\nFile:H\u00e1cs 2.jpg\nFile:H\u00e1cs 3.jpg\nFile:H\u00e1cs 5.jpg\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==Literature==\n* L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Szita : Somogy megyei nemzetis\u00e9gek telep\u00fcl\u00e9st\u00f6rt\u00e9nete a XVIII-XIX. sz\u00e1zadban - Somogyi Almanach 52. (Kaposv\u00e1r, 1993)\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.terkepcentrum.hu/index.asp?go=map&tid=18634 Street map (Hungarian)]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Somogy-geo-stub}}\n\n{{Fony\u00f3d District}}\n{{Somogy}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hacs}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Somogy County]]\n[[Category:Hungarian German communities in Somogy County]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control, removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H%C3%A1cs"}
{"title_page": "Hideji H\u014dj\u014d", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Hideji H\u014dj\u014d \n| image       = Hideji H\u014dj\u014d.jpg\n| caption     = H\u014dj\u014d Hideji\n| native_name =\u5317\u6761 \u79c0\u53f8\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1902|11|07|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Osaka]], [[Japan]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1996|5|19|1902|11|07}}\n| death_place = [[Kamakura, Kanagawa]], Japan\n| resting_place = Ryuho-ji, Kamakura\n| occupation  = Writer \n| genre       = stage plays\n| movement    = [[Shimpa]]\n| alma_mater = [[Kansai University]]\n| notableworks = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  =\n| awards = [[Shinchosha]] Prize (1941)<br>[[Yomiuri Prize|Yomiuri Literary Award]] (1965)<br>[[Kikuchi Kan Prize]] (1973)<br>Otami Keijiro Prize (1987)\n}}\n{{Japanese name|H\u014dj\u014d}}\n{{nihongo|'''Hideji H\u014dj\u014d'''|\u5317\u6761 \u79c0\u53f8|H\u014dj\u014d Hideji|extra=November 7, 1902 \u2013 May 19, 1996}} was the [[pen name]] of a [[Japanese author]], novelist, and playwright in [[Sh\u014dwa period]] [[Japan]]. His real name was {{nihongo|'''Iino Hideji'''|\u98ef\u91ce \u79c0\u4e8c||}}.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Osaka]] and a graduate of [[Kansai University]], H\u014dj\u014d moved to [[Tokyo]] in 1926 and found employment with the [[Hakone Tozan Railway]]. In 1933, he quit his job to devote his attention to [[Noh|drama]], becoming a student with [[Okamoto Kido]] and [[Hasegawa Shin]]. He became a leading member of the ''[[Shimpa]]'' modern drama movement in the 1930s.\n\nDuring [[World War II]], he was active in writing ''kokumingeki'' (government propaganda plays) such as ''[[Tamna Tunnel]]'', intended to help the war effort.<ref name = Cody>{{cite book | last = Cody| first = Gabrielle H.| authorlink = | year = 2007| title =  The Columbia Encyclopedia of Modern Drama: A-L| publisher = Columbia University Press  | location = | isbn = 0231144229}} page 621</ref>\n\nH\u014dj\u014d was author of more than 200 plays and the leader of commercial theatre in Japan after [[World War II]], working in a wide range of genres, from [[kabuki]], to ''shimpa'' and [[Takarazuka Revue]]s. In ''Behind the Flower Garden'' in 1960, he wrote a play in which actor Shotaro Hanayagi had to play both the male and female leads.<ref name = Cody/>\n\nHis psychological dramas about average citizens appealed to mainstream audiences. He is especially known for his screenplay adaptations of ''[[Miyamoto Musashi]]'', ''[[Genji Monogatari]]'', and many other [[historical fiction|historical drama]]s.\n\nH\u014dj\u014d was awarded numerous [[literary award]]s in his career, including the [[Shinchosha]] Prize, the [[Yomiuri Prize|Yomiuri Literary Award]] and the [[Kikuchi Kan Prize]]. In 1987, he was designated a [[Person of Cultural Merit]] by the Japanese government.\n\nHis grave is at the temple Ryuho-ji in [[Ofuna Station|Ofuna]], [[Kamakura, Kanagawa|Kamakura]], where he lived for many years.\n\n== Filmography ==\n* ''[[Koi sugata kitsune goten]]'' (\u604b\u3059\u304c\u305f\u72d0\u5fa1\u6bbf) (1956), writer\n\n==See also==\n*[[Japanese literature]]\n*[[List of Japanese authors]]\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book | last = Cody| first = Gabrielle H.| authorlink = | year = 2007| title =  The Columbia Encyclopedia of Modern Drama: A-L| publisher = Columbia University Press  | location = | isbn = 0231144229}}\n*{{cite book | last = Powell| first = Brian|authorlink = | year = 2002| title = Japan's Modern Theatre: A Century of Change and Continuity| publisher = RoutledgeCurzon | location = | isbn = 1873410301}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hideji H\u014dj\u014d}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928001934/http://www.n-fmellow.org/kahitokuhi/houjou.html Monuments with Hojo Hideji\u2019s poem, Tsukudajima, Tokyo]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n*{{IMDb name|id=0389921|name=Hojo Hideji}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hojo, Hideji}}\n[[Category:1902 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:Japanese dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Japanese screenwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Osaka]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Kansai University alumni]]\n[[Category:Winners of the Yomiuri Prize]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Hideji H\u014dj\u014d \n| image       = Hideji H\u014dj\u014d.jpg\n| caption     = H\u014dj\u014d Hideji\n| native_name =\u5317\u6761 \u79c0\u53f8\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1902|11|07|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Osaka]], [[Japan]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1996|5|19|1902|11|07}}\n| death_place = [[Kamakura, Kanagawa]], Japan\n| resting_place = Ryuho-ji, Kamakura\n| occupation  = Writer \n| genre       = stage plays\n| movement    = [[Shimpa]]\n| alma_mater = [[Kansai University]]\n| notableworks = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  =\n| awards = [[Shinchosha]] Prize (1941)<br>[[Yomiuri Prize|Yomiuri Literary Award]] (1965)<br>[[Kikuchi Kan Prize]] (1973)<br>Otami Keijiro Prize (1987)\n}}\n{{Japanese name|H\u014dj\u014d}}\n{{nihongo|'''Hideji H\u014dj\u014d'''|\u5317\u6761 \u79c0\u53f8|H\u014dj\u014d Hideji|extra=November 7, 1902 \u2013 May 19, 1996}} was the [[pen name]] of a [[Japanese author]], novelist, and playwright in [[Sh\u014dwa period]] [[Japan]]. His real name was {{nihongo|'''Iino Hideji'''|\u98ef\u91ce \u79c0\u4e8c||}}.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Osaka]] and a graduate of [[Kansai University]], H\u014dj\u014d moved to [[Tokyo]] in 1926 and found employment with the [[Hakone Tozan Railway]]. In 1933, he quit his job to devote his attention to [[Noh|drama]], becoming a student with [[Okamoto Kido]] and [[Hasegawa Shin]]. He became a leading member of the ''[[Shimpa]]'' modern drama movement in the 1930s.\n\nDuring [[World War II]], he was active in writing ''kokumingeki'' (government propaganda plays) such as ''[[Tamna Tunnel]]'', intended to help the war effort.<ref name = Cody>{{cite book | last = Cody| first = Gabrielle H.| authorlink = | year = 2007| title =  The Columbia Encyclopedia of Modern Drama: A-L| publisher = Columbia University Press  | location = | isbn = 0231144229}} page 621</ref>\n\nH\u014dj\u014d was author of more than 200 plays and the leader of commercial theatre in Japan after [[World War II]], working in a wide range of genres, from [[kabuki]], to ''shimpa'' and [[Takarazuka Revue]]s. In ''Behind the Flower Garden'' in 1960, he wrote a play in which actor Shotaro Hanayagi had to play both the male and female leads.<ref name = Cody/>\n\nHis psychological dramas about average citizens appealed to mainstream audiences. He is especially known for his screenplay adaptations of ''[[Miyamoto Musashi]]'', ''[[Genji Monogatari]]'', and many other [[historical fiction|historical drama]]s.\n\nH\u014dj\u014d was awarded numerous [[literary award]]s in his career, including the [[Shinchosha]] Prize, the [[Yomiuri Prize|Yomiuri Literary Award]] and the [[Kikuchi Kan Prize]]. In 1987, he was designated a [[Person of Cultural Merit]] by the Japanese government.\n\nHis grave is at the temple Ryuho-ji in [[Ofuna Station|Ofuna]], [[Kamakura, Kanagawa|Kamakura]], where he lived for many years.\n\n== Filmography ==\n* ''[[Koi sugata kitsune goten]]'' (\u604b\u3059\u304c\u305f\u72d0\u5fa1\u6bbf) (1956), writer\n\n==See also==\n*[[Japanese literature]]\n*[[List of Japanese authors]]\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book | last = Cody| first = Gabrielle H.| authorlink = | year = 2007| title =  The Columbia Encyclopedia of Modern Drama: A-L| publisher = Columbia University Press  | location = | isbn = 0231144229}}\n*{{cite book | last = Powell| first = Brian|authorlink = | year = 2002| title = Japan's Modern Theatre: A Century of Change and Continuity| publisher = RoutledgeCurzon | location = | isbn = 1873410301}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hideji H\u014dj\u014d}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928001934/http://www.n-fmellow.org/kahitokuhi/houjou.html Monuments with Hojo Hideji\u2019s poem, Tsukudajima, Tokyo]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n*{{IMDb name|id=0389921|name=Hojo Hideji}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hojo, Hideji}}\n[[Category:1902 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:Japanese writers]]\n[[Category:Japanese dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Japanese screenwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Osaka]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Kansai University alumni]]\n[[Category:Winners of the Yomiuri Prize]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotes:duplicate categorization; already in subcat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hideji_H%C5%8Dj%C5%8D"}
{"title_page": "Name of the Czech Republic", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\nThe [[Czech Republic]]'s official formal and short names at the [[United Nations]] are {{lang|cs|'''\u010cesk\u00e1 republika'''}} and {{lang|cs|'''\u010cesko'''}} in [[Czech language|Czech]], and '''the Czech Republic''' and '''Czechia''' in English.<ref name=\"UNTermDb\">{{cite web |url=https://unterm.un.org/unterm/Display/record/UNHQ/NA?Id=4275087d-4018-4082-899d-95f37efeda65 |title=The Czech Republic |website=The United Nations Terminology Database |accessdate=2 September 2016}}</ref> All these names derive from the name of the [[Czechs]], the [[West Slavs|West Slavic]] ethnic group native to the [[Czech lands]]. ''Czechia'' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t\u0283|\u025b|k|i|\u0259}}), the official English short name specified by the Czech government, is used by many international organisations and attested as early as 1841. However, most English speakers use ''[the] Czech Republic'' in all contexts.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/notes/2016/04/a-scandal-in-czechia/478635/ |title=A Scandal in Czechia |first=James |last=Fallows |date=April 22, 2016 |magazine=[[The Atlantic]] |access-date=31 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.praguepost.cz/tempo/17285-czech-out-the-proposed-name.html |title=Czech out the proposed name |first=Daniel |last=Bardsley |date=16 October 2013 |newspaper=[[The Prague Post]] |access-date=7 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508025619/http://www.praguepost.cz/tempo/17285-czech-out-the-proposed-name.html |archive-date=8 May 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Name of the Czech Republic#Other languages|Other languages]] generally have greater official use of a short form analogous to ''\u010cesko'' or ''Czechia''<ref name=\"Pavel Boh\u00e1\u010d 1993\">{{cite book |last1=Boh\u00e1\u010d |first1=Pavel |last2=Kol\u00e1\u0159 |first2=Jaroslav |date=1993 |title=Jm\u00e9na st\u00e1t\u016f a jejich \u00fazemn\u00edch \u010d\u00e1st\u00ed |trans-title=Names of states and their territorial parts |location=Praha |publisher=\u010cesk\u00fd \u00fa\u0159ad zem\u011bm\u011b\u0159ick\u00fd a katastr\u00e1ln\u00ed |language=cs |isbn=978-8-08691-857-0}}</ref><ref name=\"RoseWright\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.cz/books?id=lCdMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA496&dq=%22czechia%22&hl=cs&sa=X&ei=4nzdU6X4G4T4yQO_goH4DQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22czechia%22&f=false |title=A New General Biographical Dictionary Projected and Partly Arranged |first1=Hugh James |last1=Rose |first2=Henry John |last2=Rose |first3=Thomas |last3=Wright |date=1 January 1841 |publisher=Fellowes |accessdate=10 May 2017 |via=Google Books}}</ref> (such as French {{lang|fr|[la] Tch\u00e9quie}}, or Korean {{lang|ko|\uccb4\uc2a4\uaf2c}}/''Ches\u016dkko'' or {{lang|ko|\uccb4\ucf54}}/''Chekho'') although forms equivalent to \"Czech Republic\" are not uncommon.<!-- see choices at [https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q213] -->\n\nThe Czech name {{lang|cs|'''\u010cechy'''}} is from the same root but means [[Bohemia]], the westernmost and largest historical region of the [[Czech lands]] and the modern Czech Republic. The name ''Bohemia'' is an [[exonym]] derived from the [[Boii]], a Celtic tribe inhabiting the area before the [[early Slavs]] arrived. The [[Lands of the Bohemian Crown]] (1348\u20131918) were part of the [[Holy Roman Empire]]; often called \"the Czech lands\", they sometimes extended further, to all of [[Silesia]], [[Lusatia]], and various smaller territories. The Czech adjective {{lang|cs|'''\u010desk\u00fd'''}} means both \"Czech\" and \"Bohemian\".\n\nThe Czech Republic's official formal and short names in Czech were decided at its creation after the [[dissolution of Czechoslovakia]] in the so-called \"Velvet Divorce\" of 1993.<ref name=\"Pavel Boh\u00e1\u010d 1993\"/><ref name=\"UNGEGN World Geographical Names\">{{cite web |url=http://unstats.un.org/unsd/geoinfo/geonames/ |title=World Geographical Names database |date=25 April 2019 |website=[[UNGEGN]] |access-date=31 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.psp.cz/docs/laws/constitution.html |title=\u00dastava \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky ze dne 16. prosince 1992 |trans-title=Constitution of the Czech Republic of 16 December 1992 |website=[[Parliament of the Czech Republic]] |language=cs |accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nase-rec.ujc.cas.cz\">{{cite journal |url=http://nase-rec.ujc.cas.cz/archiv.php?art=6404 |title=\u010cesko = \u010cesk\u00e1 socialistick\u00e1 republika |first=Miloslava |last=Knappov\u00e1 |journal=Na\u0161e \u0159e\u010d |volume=66 |date=1983 |number=4 |pages=205-206 |language=cs |accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ujc.cas.cz/jazykova-poradna/porfaq.html#cesko |title=FAQ: \u010cesko |website=[[\u00dastav pro jazyk \u010desk\u00fd]] |language=cs |access-date=31 December 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309081723/http://www.ujc.cas.cz/jazykova-poradna/porfaq.html#cesko |archive-date=2013-03-09}}</ref><ref name=\"ceskoprirucka\">{{cite web |url=http://prirucka.ujc.cas.cz/?id=725 |title=\u010cesko |date=January 8, 2012 |website=Internetov\u00e1 jazykov\u00e1 p\u0159\u00edru\u010dka (IJP) [Online language guide] |language=cs |access-date=31 December 2019 \n}}</ref>\n\n== Czech-language name ==\nThe country is named after the Czechs ({{lang-cs|\u010cechov\u00e9}}), a Slavic tribe residing in central [[Bohemia]] that subdued the surrounding tribes in the late 9th century and created the Czech/Bohemian state. The origin of the name of the tribe itself is unknown. According to legend, it comes from their leader [[Lech, Czech, and Rus|\u010cech]], who brought them to Bohemia. Research regards \u010cech as a derivative of the root ''\u010del-'' (member of the people, kinsman).<ref>{{cite journal |url = http://nase-rec.ujc.cas.cz/archiv.php?art=4320 |publisher=The Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic |title = P\u016fvod jm\u00e9na \u010cech |trans-title = Origin of the name ''\u010cech'' |first=Jarom\u00edr |last=Spal |journal=Na\u0161e \u0159e\u010d (Our Speech) |pages=263\u2013267 |volume=36 |issue=9-10 |year=1953 |language = cs |access-date=11 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nSeveral variants of the name have been used over the centuries, due to the evolution of the Czech language. The digraph \"c\u017e\" was used from the time of the 16th-century ''[[Bible of Kralice]]'' until the [[Czech orthography#History|reform of 1842]], being eventually replaced by \"\u010d\" (changing ''C\u017eechy'' to ''\u010cechy''). In the late 19th century the suffix for the names of countries changed from -y to -sko (e.g. ''Rakousy''-''Rakousko'' for Austria, ''Uhry''-''Uhersko'' for Hungary). While the notion of ''\u010cesko'' appears for the first time in 1704, it only came into official use in 1918 as the first part of the name of the newly independent [[Czechoslovakia]] (''\u010cesko-Slovensko'' or ''\u010ceskoslovensko'') . Within that state, the [[Czech Socialist Republic]] (''\u010cesk\u00e1 socialistick\u00e1 republika'', ''\u010cSR'')<ref name=\"nase-rec.ujc.cas.cz\"/> was created on 1 January 1969.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.psp.cz/docs/texts/constitution_1968.html |title=\u00dastavn\u00ed z\u00e1kon ze dne 27. \u0159\u00edjna 1968 o \u010deskoslovensk\u00e9 federaci |trans-title=Constitutional Act of 27 October 1968 on the Czechoslovak Federation |website=Parliament of the Czech Republic |language=cs |accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref> On 6 March 1990 the Czech Socialist Republic was renamed the [[Czech Republic]] (''\u010cesk\u00e1 republika'', ''\u010cR'').<ref name=\"zakonyprolidi.cz\">{{cite web |url = http://www.zakonyprolidi.cz/cs/1990-53 |title = 53/1990 Sb. \u00dastavn\u00ed z\u00e1kon \u010cesk\u00e9 n\u00e1rodn\u00ed rady o zm\u011bn\u011b n\u00e1zvu \u010cesk\u00e9 socialistick\u00e9 republiky |trans-title = 53/1990 Sb. Constitutional Act of the Czech National Council on the Change of the Name of the Czech Socialist Republic |website=Z\u00e1kony pro lidi |language=cs |access-date = 10 May 2017 }}</ref> When Czechoslovakia broke up in 1993, the Czech part of the name was intended to serve as the name of the Czech state. The decision started a dispute as many perceived the \"new\" word ''\u010cesko'', which before had been only rarely used alone, as harsh sounding or as a remnant of ''\u010ceskoslovensko''.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.radio.cz/en/article/53850 |title=Looking for a name |first=Daniela |last=Lazarov\u00e1 |date=13 May 2004 |website=[[Radio Prague]] |access-date=27 January 2011 }}</ref> The older term ''\u010cechy'' was rejected by many because it was primarily associated with Bohemia proper and to use it for the whole country was seen as inappropriate. This feeling was especially prominent among the inhabitants of [[Moravia]].{{cn |date=October 2019}}\n\nThe use of the word \"\u010cesko\" within the country itself has increased in recent years.{{NoteTag|According to the official Czech list of country names: \"\u010cesko is a standardized one-word name of the state, which is officially named \u010cesk\u00e1 republika according to its constitution\".<ref name=\"Pavel Boh\u00e1\u010d 1993\" />}} During the 1990s, \"\u010cesko\" was rarely used and viewed as controversial: some Czech politicians and public figures (e.g. media magnate [[Vladim\u00edr \u017delezn\u00fd]]) expressed concern about the non-use of ''\u010cesko'' and ''Czechia''; on the other side, individuals such as president [[V\u00e1clav Havel]] and minister [[Alexandr Vondra]] have strongly opposed using these forms. In 1997, the Civic Initiative Czechia was formed by linguists and geographers in [[Brno]] to promote the use of Czechia.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.czechia-initiative.com/index.html |title = \u010cesko/Czechia |website = The Civic Initiative Czechia |access-date=10 May 2017 }}</ref> The following year, a conference of professionals aimed at encouraging the use of the name was held at [[Charles University in Prague]]. The Czech [[Senate of the Parliament of the Czech Republic|Senate]] held a session on the issue in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.senat.cz/xqw/xervlet/pssenat/htmlhled?action=doc&value=26753 |title = Funk\u010dn\u00ed rozli\u0161ov\u00e1n\u00ed spisovn\u00fdch n\u00e1zv\u016f \u010cesk\u00e1 republika a \u010cesko a jejich cizojazy\u010dn\u00fdch ekvivalent\u016f |trans-title = Functional differentiation of literary names Czech Republic and Czechia and their equivalents in foreign languages |date=11 May 2004 |website=Senate of the Czech Republic |language=cs |access-date=10 May 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"7thPublicHearing\">{{cite web |url = http://www.senat.cz/xqw/xervlet/pssenat/htmlhled?action=doc&value=27462 |title= T\u011bsnopiseck\u00fd z\u00e1znam ze 7. ve\u0159ejn\u00e9ho sly\u0161en\u00ed Sen\u00e1tu Parlamentu \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky |trans-title = Stenographic record of the 7th public hearing of the Senate of the Parliament of the Czech Republic |date=11 May 2004 |website=Senate of the Czech Republic |language=cs |access-date=10 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\n== English-language name ==\nThe historical English name of the country is Bohemia. This name derives from the Celtic tribe of [[Boii]], who inhabited the area from the 4th century BC. ''Boiohaemum'', as it was originally known in Latin, comes from the Germanic \"Boi-haima\", meaning \"home of the Boii\". The name survived all the later migrations affecting the area, including the arrival of the [[Slavs]] and the creation of the Czech state. In the 9th century, the country became officially known as the Duchy of Bohemia, changing to the Kingdom of Bohemia in the 11th century, and the Crown of Bohemia in the 14th century. A number of other names for the country have been used, including Lands of the Bohemian Crown, Czech/Bohemian lands, Bohemian Crown, the lands of the Crown of Saint Wenceslas and others.<ref name=\"\u0160itler 2017\" /><ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/fynesmorysons04moryuoft/fynesmorysons04moryuoft_djvu.txt |title=The Itinerary of Fynes Moryson Containing His Ten Yeeres Travell through the Twelve Dominions of Germany, Bohmerland, Sweitzerland, Netherland, Denmarke, Poland, Italy, Turky, France, England, Scotland & Ireland (Volume IV) |authorlink=Fynes Moryson |first=Fynes |last=Moryson |date=1908 |orig-year=1626 |location=Glasgow |publisher=[[James MacLehose and Sons]] |access-date=31 December 2019}}</ref> The Bohemian state included the three historical lands: Bohemia (''\u010cechy'') in narrower meaning, [[Moravia]] (''Morava'') and [[Silesia]] (''Slezsko''). From the 14th century until 1635 it also included Upper and Lower [[Lusatia]]. The higher hierarchical status of the Bohemian region led to that name being used for the larger country, with the people and language of this country being commonly referred to as Bohemian.\n\nThe first known usage of the word Czechia in English comes from a book of 1841 by Henry and Thomas Rose, ''A New General Biographical Dictionary Projected and Partly Arranged''.<ref name=\"RoseWright\" /><ref name=\"\u0160itler 2017\" />\n\nShortly before the disintegration of the Austro-Hungarian empire, there were proposals to use the traditional name Bohemia for the newly-formed state.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bene\u0161 |first=Edvard |authorlink=Edvard Bene\u0161 |year=1917 |title=Bohemia's case for independence |publisher=Allen & Unwin |location=London |isbn=0-405-02734-6}}</ref> However, out of consideration for Slovak national aspirations, the name \"Czecho-Slovakia\" (later \"Czechoslovakia\") was adopted instead.\n\nAfter the establishment of Czechoslovakia, the name ''Czechia'' appeared in English, alongside the official name, as a reference to all the Czech lands<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.muni.cz/research/publications/353778/ |title=Czechia = Bohemia + Moravia + Silesia |first1=Jan |last1=Munzar |first2=Milan V\u00e1clav |last2=Dr\u00e1pela |date=1999 |journal=Moravian Geographical Report |volume=7 |number=2 |pages=58-61 |location=Brno |publisher=\u00dastav Geoniky |language=cs |via=[[Masaryk University]] |access-date=31 December 2019}}</ref> and to differentiate between the Czech and [[Slovakia|Slovak]] parts of the state. It was used at least as early as 4 January 1925; appearing in the article \"Literary History of the Czechs\", published by ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://i1203.photobucket.com/albums/bb383/JanBlanicky/LiteraryhistoryoftheCzechs.jpg |title=Literary History of the Czechs |date=January 4, 1925 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref> The name was used in the Anglophone press before the German occupation of the Czech lands in 1939.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1939/03/20/archives/soviet-note-to-germany.html |title=Soviet Note to Germany |date=20 March 1939 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jpress.org.il/Olive/APA/NLI/SharedView.Article.aspx?parm=%2FwB8ANL%2BnPwlFbqqHZmiA2bODax0AAxGfBgq4FZFSaR94CtNu1UI%2FxFmhikXq9%2FgYw%3D%3D&mode=image&href=PLS%2f1939%2f12%2f28&page=6 |title=Saving The Children |date=28 December 1939 |newspaper=[[The Palestine Post]] |accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48344226 |title=Dr. Benes Broadcasts To His Countrymen |date=16 March 1940 |newspaper=[[The Barrier Miner]] |location=Broken Hill, New South Wales |page=6 |access-date=10 May 2017 |via=[[Trove]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/search/pages/results/?state=&date1=1789&date2=1943&proxtext=Czechia&x=15&y=10&dateFilterType=yearRange&rows=20&searchType=basic |title=Search results containing \"Czechia\" |website=[[Chronicling America]] |publisher=Library of Congress |access-date=31 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe current English ethnonym ''Czech'' comes from the [[Polish language|Polish]] ethnonym associated with the area, which ultimately comes from the Czech word ''\u010cech''.<ref name=\"CollinsDictionary\">{{cite dictionary |url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/czech |title=Czech definition and meaning |dictionary=[[Collins English Dictionary]] |publisher=[[HarperCollins]] |accessdate=19 November 2012 |quote=C19: from Polish, from Czech ''\u010cech''}}</ref><ref name=\"American Heritage Dictionary\">{{cite dictionary |url=https://ahdictionary.com/word/search.html?q=Czech |title=Czech |dictionary=[[American Heritage Dictionary]] |publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]] |accessdate=24 January 2018 |quote=Polish, from Czech ''\u010cech''.}}</ref><ref name=\"OxfordDictionary\">{{cite dictionary |url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/czech |title=Czech - Definition in English |dictionary=[[Oxford English Dictionary]] |publisher=[[Oxford University]] |accessdate=11 April 2018 |quote=Origin Polish spelling of Czech ''\u010cech''.}}</ref> The words \"Czechian\", \"Czechish\", \"Czechic\" and later \"Czech\" (using antiquated Czech spelling)<ref name=\"\u0160itler 2017\" /> have appeared in English-language texts since the 17th century. During the 19th-century national revival, the word \"Czech\" was also used to distinguish between the Czech- and German-speaking peoples living in the country. The term \"Czechia\" is attested as early as 1569 in Latin<ref name=\"\u0160itler 2017\">{{cite news |url=http://www.pressreader.com/czech-republic/lidove-noviny/20170701/281973197671948 |title=Czechia si to bude muset protrp\u011bt |trans-title=Czechia will have to endure it |last=\u0160itler |first=Ji\u0159\u00ed |date=July 1, 2017 |newspaper=[[Lidov\u00e9 noviny]] |language=Czech |access-date=July 6, 2017 |via=[[PressReader]]}}</ref> and 1841 in English (''Poselkynie starych Przjbiehuw Czeskych \u2013 Messenger of the old Fates of Czechia'').<ref name=\"RoseWright\" /><ref name=\"\u0160itler 2017\" /> There were other early mentions in 1856<ref name=\"N&Q\">{{cite journal |ref=harv |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wbs9AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA20 |title=Replies to Minor Queries |journal=[[Notes and Queries]] |volume=II |number=27 |page=20 |year=July 1856 |publisher=Oxford University Press |access-date=31 December 2019}}</ref> and in an 1866 report on the [[Austro-Prussian War]].<ref name=\"Berlin1866\">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8840587 |title=Latest From Prussia |date=21 July 1866 |newspaper=[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]] |location=Hobart, Tasmania |access-date=10 May 2017 |page=4 |via=Trove}}</ref>\n\n===Adoption of ''Czechia''===\nIn accordance with Resolution No. 4 I. of the UN conference on the standardization of geographic names (Geneva 1967) and Resolution No. 2 III. of the UN conference on the standardization of geographic names (Athens 1977), the Terminological Committee of the Czech Office for Surveying, Mapping, and Cadaster in cooperation with the Czech Ministry of Foreign Affairs standardized ''Czechia'' as the English translation of ''\u010cesko'' in early 1993.<ref name=\"Pavel Boh\u00e1\u010d 1993\"/>\n\nOther names suggested in the 1990s included ''Czechomoravia'' or ''Czechlands''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-05-10/news/9805100369_1_czech-republic-czechomoravia-moravia-and-silesia |title=After 5 Years, Czech Republic Still Searching for a Short Name |first=David |last=Rocks |date=May 10, 1998 |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |access-date=31 December 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170107171154/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-05-10/news/9805100369_1_czech-republic-czechomoravia-moravia-and-silesia |archive-date=January 7, 2017}}</ref> However, by 2000 a short name had still not been fully adopted by the Czech authorities. At that time, the Second Secretary, Press and Politics at the British Embassy in Prague, Giles Portman, showed a willingness to accept the name ''Czechia''. Portman said in 2000, \"Czechs still use the name ''\u010cesk\u00e1 republika'' rather than ''\u010cesko'', and the English equivalent, ''the Czech Republic'', rather than ''Czechia''. Were that pattern to change, we would have no problem at all with adapting accordingly. But we feel that the initiative for that change must come from the Czech side and not from us.\"{{NoteTag|Record of Proceedings of the 7th Public Hearing of the Senate, 11 May 2004, recording Portman's letter from 4 April 2000 from the British embassy in Prague.<ref name=\"7thPublicHearing\" />}}\n\nIn 2013, Czech president [[Milo\u0161 Zeman]] recommended the wider official use of ''Czechia'',<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/whats-in-a-name-czech-republic-mulls-shock-rebranding-as-czechia-8874839.html |title = What's in a name? Czech Republic mulls shock rebranding as Czechia |first=Charlotte |last=McDonald-Gibson |date=11 October 2013 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |access-date=10 May 2017 }}</ref> and on 14 April 2016, the government agreed to make ''Czechia'' the official short name.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/czechia-czech-republic-new-name-english-speakers-a7323596.html |title = Czechia: English speakers told to use new name for Czech Republic |first=Tom |last=Embury-Dennis |date=22 September 2016 |newspaper=The Independent |access-date=31 December 2019 }}</ref> The new name was approved by the Czech cabinet on 2 May 2016 and registered on 5 July 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.mzv.cz/jnp/cz/udalosti_a_media/archiv_zprav/rok_2016/tiskove_zpravy/x_2016_05_02_vlada_schvalila_czechia.html |title = Vl\u00e1da schv\u00e1lila doplnen\u00ed jednoslovn\u00e9ho n\u00e1zvu Cesko v ciz\u00edch jazyc\u00edch do datab\u00e1z\u00ed OSN |trans-title = The government has approved the addition of one-word Czech name in foreign languages to UN databases |date=2 May 2016 |website=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Czech Republic)|Ministerstvo zahrani\u010dn\u00edch v\u011bc\u00ed \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky]] |language=Czech |access-date=28 August 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url = https://www.forbes.com/sites/francistapon/2017/05/22/czechia-has-won-the-czech-republic-name-debate/#5c9d94527d66 |title=Czechia Has Won The Czech Republic Name Debate |first=Francis |last=Tapon |date=May 22, 2017 |magazine=[[Forbes]] |access-date=31 December 2019 }}</ref> In November 2016 the Ministry of Foreign Affairs presented recommendations on how to use the short name \"Czechia\" in international contexts.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.mzv.cz/jnp/en/foreign_relations/public_diplomacy/digital_diplomacy/how_to_use_the_short_country_name.html |title = How to Use the Short Country name \"Czechia\" |date=11 November 2016 |website=Ministry of Foreign Affairs |access-date=31 December 2019 }}</ref> On 1 June 2017, the geography department of the Faculty of Sciences of [[Charles University]] in Prague organised a special conference to assess the progress of the name's proliferation.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.radio.cz/en/section/panorama/czechia-mapping-progress-one-year-on |title = Czechia: mapping progress one year on |first=Ruth |last=Fra\u0148kov\u00e1 |date=8 June 2017 |website=Radio Prague |access-date=24 January 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe new short name was published in the United Nations UNTERM and UNGEGN country name databases on 17 May 2016.<ref name=\"UNTermDb\" /><ref name=\"UNGEGN World Geographical Names\" /><ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.mzv.cz/jnp/en/issues_and_press/factsheets/x2016_04_21_the_completion_of_translations_of_the.html |title=Short country name \"\u010cesko\"/\"Czechia\" to be entered in UN databases |date=21 April 2016 |website=Ministry of Foreign Affairs |access-date=31 December 2019 }}</ref> In September 2016, the British [[Permanent Committee on Geographical Names for British Official Use|Permanent Committee on Geographical Names]] (PCGN) recommended the use of ''Czechia'' and added it as the sole form of the country name to their list of country names.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/554812/Czechia_Information_Paper-Updated_September_2016.pdf |title = Czechia: New English-language country name for the Czech Republic |date=September 2016 |website=Permanent Committee on Geographical Names |access-date=31 December 2019 }}</ref> On 26 September 2016, the [[International Organization for Standardization]] included the short name ''Czechia'' in the official ISO 3166 country codes list.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:CZ |title = CZ: ISO 3166 codes for the representation of names of countries and their subdivisions |website=International Organization for Standardization |access-date=31 December 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/weather/2016/apr/14/czech-republic-czechia-new-name |title=Czech Republic officials say country would like to be called 'Czechia' instead |first=Oliver |last=Laughland |date=14 April 2016 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=31 December 2019}}</ref> The name ''Czechia'' and its respective translations are also included in the interinstitutional style guide of the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://publications.europa.eu/code/en/en-370100.htm |title = Interinstitutional style guide: Countries, Designations and abbreviations to use |website = [[Europa (web portal)|Europa.eu]] |access-date=2018-09-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://publications.europa.eu/code/en/en-000300.htm |title = News: Latest modifications |date=18 September 2018 |website=Europa |access-date=2018-09-21 }}</ref>\n\nMultinational technology companies that adopted the name ''Czechia'' include [[Google]]<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.idnes.cz/technet/software/czechia-google-mapy-maps-oficial-name-czech-republic-czechia.A170120_084107_tec-kratke-zpravy_pka |title = A je to \"ofici\u00e1ln\u00ed\". Mapy Google za\u010daly \u010cesku \u0159\u00edkat Czechia |trans-title = And it's \"official\". Google Maps calls \u010cesko Czechia |date=2017-01-20 |website=[[Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|iDNES]] |language=cs |access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref> and [[Apple Inc.|Apple]].<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/19/world/africa/swaziland-eswatini-name-change.html |title=Swaziland's King Wants His Country to Be Called eSwatini |last=Chan |first=Sewell |date=April 19, 2018 |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=31 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Other languages==\n{{refimprove section|date=October 2019}}\nThe equivalent of the Czech short form {{lang|cs|\u010cesko}} is in routine use by most other languages. In a few cases (for example [[Polish language|Polish]] {{lang|pl|Czechy}}, [[Croatian language|Croatian]] {{lang|sh|\u010ce\u0161ka}} and [[Serbian language|Serbian]] {{lang|sh|\u0427\u0435\u0448\u043a\u0430/\u010ce\u0161ka}}) this form had historically been used for Bohemia. Other languages adopted new short forms such as {{lang|ar|\u062a\u0634\u064a\u0643\u064a\u0627}} ''Tsh\u012bky\u0101'' in [[Arabic]].<!--Note that the example {{lang|zh|\u6377\u514b}} (''Ji\u00e9k\u00e8'' in [[Standard Mandarin|Mandarin]]) in [[Chinese language|Chinese]] does not make sense in this context because the exact same Chinese characters have been used to translate the Czech part of Czechoslovakia--> In most cases, the new form has more or less completely replaced the formal name for most usages. However, usage in Spanish and French remains mixed, with the forms {{lang|es|Chequia}} and {{lang|fr|Tch\u00e9quie}} occasionally being used alongside the longer formal names {{lang|es|Rep\u00fablica Checa}} and {{lang|fr|R\u00e9publique tch\u00e8que}}.\n\n===German===\nIn German, the term applicable to the Czech part of Czechoslovakia used to be {{lang|de|Tschechei}}, comparable to {{lang|de|Slowakei}} for [[Slovakia]]. However, the term began to have negative connotations in connection with the [[Nazis]], who used the term {{lang|de|Rest-Tschechei}} \"[[rump state|remaining]] Czechia\" when [[Munich Agreement|they annexed the border regions of western Czechoslovakia in 1938]]. Since the end of the Second World War, the term {{lang|de|Tschechien}} has been used instead, as suggested by the Czech Ministry of Foreign Affairs as well as German and Austrian linguists. {{lang|de|Tschechien}} is a term from the 19th century that was originally used for the Czech lands that were part of [[Austria-Hungary]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.czech-tourist.de/tschechei.htm |title=Zum Begriff \"Tschechei\": Problematik und Sprachgebrauch |trans-title=About the term \"Czech Republic\": Issues and use of language |website=Czech Tourist |language=de |accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref> The German [[Federal Foreign Office]] uses Tschechien in its official list of countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.auswaertiges-amt.de/DE/Aussenpolitik/Laender/Laenderinfos/01-Nodes_Uebersichtsseiten/TschechischeRepublik_node.html |title=Tschechien |website=[[Federal Foreign Office|Ausw\u00e4rtiges Amt]] |language=de |accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bohemian]]\n* [[Hyphen War]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|Czech Republic}}\n*{{in lang|cs}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191931/https://www.national-geographic.cz/detail.asp?id=952 \"Open letter to the Czech Olympic Foundation, Czech Sports Union, politicians, business people, media, etc.\"], ''National Geographic'', 2001.\n*{{in lang|en}} [http://www.radio.cz/en/article/53850 \"Looking for a name\"] by Daniela Lazarova, Radio Prague, 13 May 2004.\n*{{in lang|en}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20110807053615/http://historia.arch.p.lodz.pl/jw37/EUROPE/cesko1.htm \"\u010cesko versus Czechy? On the geographic name of the Czech Republic\"] by Leo\u0161 Jele\u010dek, paper presented at the 2nd Slovak-Czech-Polish Geographical Seminar, Bratislava, 1\u20135 September 1999.{{dead link |date=September 2017}}\n* {{in lang|en}} [http://www.radio.cz/en/section/letter/from-bohemia-to-czechia \"From Bohemia to Czechia\"] Ji\u0159\u00ed \u0160itler (12 July 2016) [[Radio Prague]]\n\n{{Europe topic|Name of}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Geographical naming disputes|Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Names of places in Europe]]\n[[Category:Country name etymology|Czech Republic]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\nThe [[Czech Republic]]'s official formal and short names at the [[United Nations]] are {{lang|cs|'''\u010cesk\u00e1 republika'''}} and {{lang|cs|'''\u010cesko'''}} in [[Czech language|Czech]], and '''the Czech Republic''' and '''Czechia''' in English.<ref name=\"UNTermDb\">{{cite web |url=https://unterm.un.org/unterm/Display/record/UNHQ/NA?Id=4275087d-4018-4082-899d-95f37efeda65 |title=The Czech Republic |website=The United Nations Terminology Database |accessdate=2 September 2016}}</ref> All these names derive from the name of the [[Czechs]], the [[West Slavs|West Slavic]] ethnic group native to the [[Czech lands]]. ''Czechia'' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t\u0283|\u025b|k|i|\u0259}}), the official English short name specified by the Czech government, is used by many international organisations and attested as early as 1841. However, most English speakers use ''[the] Czech Republic'' in all contexts.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/notes/2016/04/a-scandal-in-czechia/478635/ |title=A Scandal in Czechia |first=James |last=Fallows |date=April 22, 2016 |magazine=[[The Atlantic]] |access-date=31 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.praguepost.cz/tempo/17285-czech-out-the-proposed-name.html |title=Czech out the proposed name |first=Daniel |last=Bardsley |date=16 October 2013 |newspaper=[[The Prague Post]] |access-date=7 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508025619/http://www.praguepost.cz/tempo/17285-czech-out-the-proposed-name.html |archive-date=8 May 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Name of the Czech Republic#Other languages|Other languages]] generally have greater official use of a short form analogous to ''\u010cesko'' or ''Czechia''<ref name=\"Pavel Boh\u00e1\u010d 1993\">{{cite book |last1=Boh\u00e1\u010d |first1=Pavel |last2=Kol\u00e1\u0159 |first2=Jaroslav |date=1993 |title=Jm\u00e9na st\u00e1t\u016f a jejich \u00fazemn\u00edch \u010d\u00e1st\u00ed |trans-title=Names of states and their territorial parts |location=Praha |publisher=\u010cesk\u00fd \u00fa\u0159ad zem\u011bm\u011b\u0159ick\u00fd a katastr\u00e1ln\u00ed |language=cs |isbn=978-8-08691-857-0}}</ref><ref name=\"RoseWright\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.cz/books?id=lCdMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA496&dq=%22czechia%22&hl=cs&sa=X&ei=4nzdU6X4G4T4yQO_goH4DQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22czechia%22&f=false |title=A New General Biographical Dictionary Projected and Partly Arranged |first1=Hugh James |last1=Rose |first2=Henry John |last2=Rose |first3=Thomas |last3=Wright |date=1 January 1841 |publisher=Fellowes |accessdate=10 May 2017 |via=Google Books}}</ref> (such as French {{lang|fr|[la] Tch\u00e9quie}}, or Korean {{lang|ko|\uccb4\uc2a4\uaf2c}}/''Ches\u016dkko'' or {{lang|ko|\uccb4\ucf54}}/''Chekho'') although forms equivalent to \"Czech Republic\" are not uncommon.<!-- see choices at [https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q213] -->\n\nThe Czech name {{lang|cs|'''\u010cechy'''}} is from the same root but means [[Bohemia]], the westernmost and largest historical region of the [[Czech lands]] and the modern Czech Republic. The name ''Bohemia'' is an [[exonym]] derived from the [[Boii]], a Celtic tribe inhabiting the area before the [[early Slavs]] arrived. The [[Lands of the Bohemian Crown]] (1348\u20131918) were part of the [[Holy Roman Empire]]; often called \"the Czech lands\", they sometimes extended further, to all of [[Silesia]], [[Lusatia]], and various smaller territories. The Czech adjective {{lang|cs|'''\u010desk\u00fd'''}} means both \"Czech\" and \"Bohemian\".\n\nThe Czech Republic's official formal and short names in Czech were decided at its creation after the [[dissolution of Czechoslovakia]] in the so-called \"Velvet Divorce\" of 1993.<ref name=\"Pavel Boh\u00e1\u010d 1993\"/><ref name=\"UNGEGN World Geographical Names\">{{cite web |url=http://unstats.un.org/unsd/geoinfo/geonames/ |title=World Geographical Names database |date=25 April 2019 |website=[[UNGEGN]] |access-date=31 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.psp.cz/docs/laws/constitution.html |title=\u00dastava \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky ze dne 16. prosince 1992 |trans-title=Constitution of the Czech Republic of 16 December 1992 |website=[[Parliament of the Czech Republic]] |language=cs |accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nase-rec.ujc.cas.cz\">{{cite journal |url=http://nase-rec.ujc.cas.cz/archiv.php?art=6404 |title=\u010cesko = \u010cesk\u00e1 socialistick\u00e1 republika |first=Miloslava |last=Knappov\u00e1 |journal=Na\u0161e \u0159e\u010d |volume=66 |date=1983 |number=4 |pages=205-206 |language=cs |accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ujc.cas.cz/jazykova-poradna/porfaq.html#cesko |title=FAQ: \u010cesko |website=[[\u00dastav pro jazyk \u010desk\u00fd]] |language=cs |access-date=31 December 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309081723/http://www.ujc.cas.cz/jazykova-poradna/porfaq.html#cesko |archive-date=2013-03-09}}</ref><ref name=\"ceskoprirucka\">{{cite web |url=http://prirucka.ujc.cas.cz/?id=725 |title=\u010cesko |date=January 8, 2012 |website=Internetov\u00e1 jazykov\u00e1 p\u0159\u00edru\u010dka (IJP) [Online language guide] |language=cs |access-date=31 December 2019 \n}}</ref>\n\n== Czech-language name ==\nThe country is named after the Czechs ({{lang-cs|\u010cechov\u00e9}}), a Slavic tribe residing in central [[Bohemia]] that subdued the surrounding tribes in the late 9th century and created the Czech/Bohemian state. The origin of the name of the tribe itself is unknown. According to legend, it comes from their leader [[Lech, Czech, and Rus|\u010cech]], who brought them to Bohemia. Research regards \u010cech as a derivative of the root ''\u010del-'' (member of the people, kinsman).<ref>{{cite journal |url = http://nase-rec.ujc.cas.cz/archiv.php?art=4320 |publisher=The Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic |title = P\u016fvod jm\u00e9na \u010cech |trans-title = Origin of the name ''\u010cech'' |first=Jarom\u00edr |last=Spal |journal=Na\u0161e \u0159e\u010d (Our Speech) |pages=263\u2013267 |volume=36 |issue=9-10 |year=1953 |language = cs |access-date=11 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nSeveral variants of the name have been used over the centuries, due to the evolution of the Czech language. The digraph \"c\u017e\" was used from the time of the 16th-century ''[[Bible of Kralice]]'' until the [[Czech orthography#History|reform of 1842]], being eventually replaced by \"\u010d\" (changing ''C\u017eechy'' to ''\u010cechy''). In the late 19th century the suffix for the names of countries changed from -y to -sko (e.g. ''Rakousy''-''Rakousko'' for Austria, ''Uhry''-''Uhersko'' for Hungary). While the notion of ''\u010cesko'' appears for the first time in 1704, it only came into official use in 1918 as the first part of the name of the newly independent [[Czechoslovakia]] (''\u010cesko-Slovensko'' or ''\u010ceskoslovensko'') . Within that state, the [[Czech Socialist Republic]] (''\u010cesk\u00e1 socialistick\u00e1 republika'', ''\u010cSR'')<ref name=\"nase-rec.ujc.cas.cz\"/> was created on 1 January 1969.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.psp.cz/docs/texts/constitution_1968.html |title=\u00dastavn\u00ed z\u00e1kon ze dne 27. \u0159\u00edjna 1968 o \u010deskoslovensk\u00e9 federaci |trans-title=Constitutional Act of 27 October 1968 on the Czechoslovak Federation |website=Parliament of the Czech Republic |language=cs |accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref> On 6 March 1990 the Czech Socialist Republic was renamed the [[Czech Republic]] (''\u010cesk\u00e1 republika'', ''\u010cR'').<ref name=\"zakonyprolidi.cz\">{{cite web |url = http://www.zakonyprolidi.cz/cs/1990-53 |title = 53/1990 Sb. \u00dastavn\u00ed z\u00e1kon \u010cesk\u00e9 n\u00e1rodn\u00ed rady o zm\u011bn\u011b n\u00e1zvu \u010cesk\u00e9 socialistick\u00e9 republiky |trans-title = 53/1990 Sb. Constitutional Act of the Czech National Council on the Change of the Name of the Czech Socialist Republic |website=Z\u00e1kony pro lidi |language=cs |access-date = 10 May 2017 }}</ref> When Czechoslovakia broke up in 1993, the Czech part of the name was intended to serve as the name of the Czech state. The decision started a dispute as many perceived the \"new\" word ''\u010cesko'', which before had been only rarely used alone, as harsh sounding or as a remnant of ''\u010ceskoslovensko''.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.radio.cz/en/article/53850 |title=Looking for a name |first=Daniela |last=Lazarov\u00e1 |date=13 May 2004 |website=[[Radio Prague]] |access-date=27 January 2011 }}</ref> The older term ''\u010cechy'' was rejected by many because it was primarily associated with Bohemia proper and to use it for the whole country was seen as inappropriate. This feeling was especially prominent among the inhabitants of [[Moravia]].{{cn |date=October 2019}}\n\nThe use of the word \"\u010cesko\" within the country itself has increased in recent years.{{NoteTag|According to the official Czech list of country names: \"\u010cesko is a standardized one-word name of the state, which is officially named \u010cesk\u00e1 republika according to its constitution\".<ref name=\"Pavel Boh\u00e1\u010d 1993\" />}} During the 1990s, \"\u010cesko\" was rarely used and viewed as controversial: some Czech politicians and public figures (e.g. media magnate [[Vladim\u00edr \u017delezn\u00fd]]) expressed concern about the non-use of ''\u010cesko'' and ''Czechia''; on the other side, individuals such as president [[V\u00e1clav Havel]] and minister [[Alexandr Vondra]] have strongly opposed using these forms. In 1997, the Civic Initiative Czechia was formed by linguists and geographers in [[Brno]] to promote the use of Czechia.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.czechia-initiative.com/index.html |title = \u010cesko/Czechia |website = The Civic Initiative Czechia |access-date=10 May 2017 }}</ref> The following year, a conference of professionals aimed at encouraging the use of the name was held at [[Charles University in Prague]]. The Czech [[Senate of the Parliament of the Czech Republic|Senate]] held a session on the issue in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.senat.cz/xqw/xervlet/pssenat/htmlhled?action=doc&value=26753 |title = Funk\u010dn\u00ed rozli\u0161ov\u00e1n\u00ed spisovn\u00fdch n\u00e1zv\u016f \u010cesk\u00e1 republika a \u010cesko a jejich cizojazy\u010dn\u00fdch ekvivalent\u016f |trans-title = Functional differentiation of literary names Czech Republic and Czechia and their equivalents in foreign languages |date=11 May 2004 |website=Senate of the Czech Republic |language=cs |access-date=10 May 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"7thPublicHearing\">{{cite web |url = http://www.senat.cz/xqw/xervlet/pssenat/htmlhled?action=doc&value=27462 |title.= T\u011bsnopiseck\u00fd z\u00e1znam ze 7. ve\u0159ejn\u00e9ho sly\u0161en\u00ed Sen\u00e1tu Parlamentu \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky |trans-title = Stenographic record of the 7th public hearing of the Senate of the Parliament of the Czech Republic |date=11 May 2004 |website=Senate of the Czech Republic |language=cs |access-date=10 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\n== English-language name ==\nThe historical English name of the country is Bohemia. This name derives from the Celtic tribe of [[Boii]], who inhabited the area from the 4th century BC. ''Boiohaemum'', as it was originally known in Latin, comes from the Germanic \"Boi-haima\", meaning \"home of the Boii\". The name survived all the later migrations affecting the area, including the arrival of the [[Slavs]] and the creation of the Czech state. In the 9th century, the country became officially known as the Duchy of Bohemia, changing to the Kingdom of Bohemia in the 11th century, and the Crown of Bohemia in the 14th century. A number of other names for the country have been used, including Lands of the Bohemian Crown, Czech/Bohemian lands, Bohemian Crown, the lands of the Crown of Saint Wenceslas and others.<ref name=\"\u0160itler 2017\" /><ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/fynesmorysons04moryuoft/fynesmorysons04moryuoft_djvu.txt |title=The Itinerary of Fynes Moryson Containing His Ten Yeeres Travell through the Twelve Dominions of Germany, Bohmerland, Sweitzerland, Netherland, Denmarke, Poland, Italy, Turky, France, England, Scotland & Ireland (Volume IV) |authorlink=Fynes Moryson |first=Fynes |last=Moryson |date=1908 |orig-year=1626 |location=Glasgow |publisher=[[James MacLehose and Sons]] |access-date=31 December 2019}}</ref> The Bohemian state included the three historical lands: Bohemia (''\u010cechy'') in narrower meaning, [[Moravia]] (''Morava'') and [[Silesia]] (''Slezsko''). From the 14th century until 1635 it also included Upper and Lower [[Lusatia]]. The higher hierarchical status of the Bohemian region led to that name being used for the larger country, with the people and language of this country being commonly referred to as Bohemian.\n\nThe first known usage of the word Czechia in English comes from a book of 1841 by Henry and Thomas Rose, ''A New General Biographical Dictionary Projected and Partly Arranged''.<ref name=\"RoseWright\" /><ref name=\"\u0160itler 2017\" />\n\nShortly before the disintegration of the Austro-Hungarian empire, there were proposals to use the traditional name Bohemia for the newly-formed state.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bene\u0161 |first=Edvard |authorlink=Edvard Bene\u0161 |year=1917 |title=Bohemia's case for independence |publisher=Allen & Unwin |location=London |isbn=0-405-02734-6}}</ref> However, out of consideration for Slovak national aspirations, the name \"Czecho-Slovakia\" (later \"Czechoslovakia\") was adopted instead.\n\nAfter the establishment of Czechoslovakia, the name ''Czechia'' appeared in English, alongside the official name, as a reference to all the Czech lands<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.muni.cz/research/publications/353778/ |title=Czechia = Bohemia + Moravia + Silesia |first1=Jan |last1=Munzar |first2=Milan V\u00e1clav |last2=Dr\u00e1pela |date=1999 |journal=Moravian Geographical Report |volume=7 |number=2 |pages=58-61 |location=Brno |publisher=\u00dastav Geoniky |language=cs |via=[[Masaryk University]] |access-date=31 December 2019}}</ref> and to differentiate between the Czech and [[Slovakia|Slovak]] parts of the state. It was used at least as early as 4 January 1925; appearing in the article \"Literary History of the Czechs\", published by ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://i1203.photobucket.com/albums/bb383/JanBlanicky/LiteraryhistoryoftheCzechs.jpg |title=Literary History of the Czechs |date=January 4, 1925 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref> The name was used in the Anglophone press before the German occupation of the Czech lands in 1939.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1939/03/20/archives/soviet-note-to-germany.html |title=Soviet Note to Germany |date=20 March 1939 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jpress.org.il/Olive/APA/NLI/SharedView.Article.aspx?parm=%2FwB8ANL%2BnPwlFbqqHZmiA2bODax0AAxGfBgq4FZFSaR94CtNu1UI%2FxFmhikXq9%2FgYw%3D%3D&mode=image&href=PLS%2f1939%2f12%2f28&page=6 |title=Saving The Children |date=28 December 1939 |newspaper=[[The Palestine Post]] |accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48344226 |title=Dr. Benes Broadcasts To His Countrymen |date=16 March 1940 |newspaper=[[The Barrier Miner]] |location=Broken Hill, New South Wales |page=6 |access-date=10 May 2017 |via=[[Trove]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/search/pages/results/?state=&date1=1789&date2=1943&proxtext=Czechia&x=15&y=10&dateFilterType=yearRange&rows=20&searchType=basic |title=Search results containing \"Czechia\" |website=[[Chronicling America]] |publisher=Library of Congress |access-date=31 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe current English ethnonym ''Czech'' comes from the [[Polish language|Polish]] ethnonym associated with the area, which ultimately comes from the Czech word ''\u010cech''.<ref name=\"CollinsDictionary\">{{cite dictionary |url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/czech |title=Czech definition and meaning |dictionary=[[Collins English Dictionary]] |publisher=[[HarperCollins]] |accessdate=19 November 2012 |quote=C19: from Polish, from Czech ''\u010cech''}}</ref><ref name=\"American Heritage Dictionary\">{{cite dictionary |url=https://ahdictionary.com/word/search.html?q=Czech |title=Czech |dictionary=[[American Heritage Dictionary]] |publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]] |accessdate=24 January 2018 |quote=Polish, from Czech ''\u010cech''.}}</ref><ref name=\"OxfordDictionary\">{{cite dictionary |url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/czech |title=Czech - Definition in English |dictionary=[[Oxford English Dictionary]] |publisher=[[Oxford University]] |accessdate=11 April 2018 |quote=Origin Polish spelling of Czech ''\u010cech''.}}</ref> The words \"Czechian\", \"Czechish\", \"Czechic\" and later \"Czech\" (using antiquated Czech spelling)<ref name=\"\u0160itler 2017\" /> have appeared in English-language texts since the 17th century. During the 19th-century national revival, the word \"Czech\" was also used to distinguish between the Czech- and German-speaking peoples living in the country. The term \"Czechia\" is attested as early as 1569 in Latin<ref name=\"\u0160itler 2017\">{{cite news |url=http://www.pressreader.com/czech-republic/lidove-noviny/20170701/281973197671948 |title=Czechia si to bude muset protrp\u011bt |trans-title=Czechia will have to endure it |last=\u0160itler |first=Ji\u0159\u00ed |date=July 1, 2017 |newspaper=[[Lidov\u00e9 noviny]] |language=Czech |access-date=July 6, 2017 |via=[[PressReader]]}}</ref> and 1841 in English (''Poselkynie starych Przjbiehuw Czeskych \u2013 Messenger of the old Fates of Czechia'').<ref name=\"RoseWright\" /><ref name=\"\u0160itler 2017\" /> There were other early mentions in 1856<ref name=\"N&Q\">{{cite journal |ref=harv |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wbs9AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA20 |title=Replies to Minor Queries |journal=[[Notes and Queries]] |volume=II |number=27 |page=20 |year=July 1856 |publisher=Oxford University Press |access-date=31 December 2019}}</ref> and in an 1866 report on the [[Austro-Prussian War]].<ref name=\"Berlin1866\">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8840587 |title=Latest From Prussia |date=21 July 1866 |newspaper=[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]] |location=Hobart, Tasmania |access-date=10 May 2017 |page=4 |via=Trove}}</ref>\n\n===Adoption of ''Czechia''===\nIn accordance with Resolution No. 4 I. of the UN conference on the standardization of geographic names (Geneva 1967) and Resolution No. 2 III. of the UN conference on the standardization of geographic names (Athens 1977), the Terminological Committee of the Czech Office for Surveying, Mapping, and Cadaster in cooperation with the Czech Ministry of Foreign Affairs standardized ''Czechia'' as the English translation of ''\u010cesko'' in early 1993.<ref name=\"Pavel Boh\u00e1\u010d 1993\"/>\n\nOther names suggested in the 1990s included ''Czechomoravia'' or ''Czechlands''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-05-10/news/9805100369_1_czech-republic-czechomoravia-moravia-and-silesia |title=After 5 Years, Czech Republic Still Searching for a Short Name |first=David |last=Rocks |date=May 10, 1998 |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |access-date=31 December 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170107171154/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-05-10/news/9805100369_1_czech-republic-czechomoravia-moravia-and-silesia |archive-date=January 7, 2017}}</ref> However, by 2000 a short name had still not been fully adopted by the Czech authorities. At that time, the Second Secretary, Press and Politics at the British Embassy in Prague, Giles Portman, showed a willingness to accept the name ''Czechia''. Portman said in 2000, \"Czechs still use the name ''\u010cesk\u00e1 republika'' rather than ''\u010cesko'', and the English equivalent, ''the Czech Republic'', rather than ''Czechia''. Were that pattern to change, we would have no problem at all with adapting accordingly. But we feel that the initiative for that change must come from the Czech side and not from us.\"{{NoteTag|Record of Proceedings of the 7th Public Hearing of the Senate, 11 May 2004, recording Portman's letter from 4 April 2000 from the British embassy in Prague.<ref name=\"7thPublicHearing\" />}}\n\nIn 2013, Czech president [[Milo\u0161 Zeman]] recommended the wider official use of ''Czechia'',<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/whats-in-a-name-czech-republic-mulls-shock-rebranding-as-czechia-8874839.html |title = What's in a name? Czech Republic mulls shock rebranding as Czechia |first=Charlotte |last=McDonald-Gibson |date=11 October 2013 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |access-date=10 May 2017 }}</ref> and on 14 April 2016, the government agreed to make ''Czechia'' the official short name.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/czechia-czech-republic-new-name-english-speakers-a7323596.html |title = Czechia: English speakers told to use new name for Czech Republic |first=Tom |last=Embury-Dennis |date=22 September 2016 |newspaper=The Independent |access-date=31 December 2019 }}</ref> The new name was approved by the Czech cabinet on 2 May 2016 and registered on 5 July 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.mzv.cz/jnp/cz/udalosti_a_media/archiv_zprav/rok_2016/tiskove_zpravy/x_2016_05_02_vlada_schvalila_czechia.html |title = Vl\u00e1da schv\u00e1lila doplnen\u00ed jednoslovn\u00e9ho n\u00e1zvu Cesko v ciz\u00edch jazyc\u00edch do datab\u00e1z\u00ed OSN |trans-title = The government has approved the addition of one-word Czech name in foreign languages to UN databases |date=2 May 2016 |website=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Czech Republic)|Ministerstvo zahrani\u010dn\u00edch v\u011bc\u00ed \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky]] |language=Czech |access-date=28 August 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url = https://www.forbes.com/sites/francistapon/2017/05/22/czechia-has-won-the-czech-republic-name-debate/#5c9d94527d66 |title=Czechia Has Won The Czech Republic Name Debate |first=Francis |last=Tapon |date=May 22, 2017 |magazine=[[Forbes]] |access-date=31 December 2019 }}</ref> In November 2016 the Ministry of Foreign Affairs presented recommendations on how to use the short name \"Czechia\" in international contexts.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.mzv.cz/jnp/en/foreign_relations/public_diplomacy/digital_diplomacy/how_to_use_the_short_country_name.html |title = How to Use the Short Country name \"Czechia\" |date=11 November 2016 |website=Ministry of Foreign Affairs |access-date=31 December 2019 }}</ref> On 1 June 2017, the geography department of the Faculty of Sciences of [[Charles University]] in Prague organised a special conference to assess the progress of the name's proliferation.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.radio.cz/en/section/panorama/czechia-mapping-progress-one-year-on |title = Czechia: mapping progress one year on |first=Ruth |last=Fra\u0148kov\u00e1 |date=8 June 2017 |website=Radio Prague |access-date=24 January 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe new short name was published in the United Nations UNTERM and UNGEGN country name databases on 17 May 2016.<ref name=\"UNTermDb\" /><ref name=\"UNGEGN World Geographical Names\" /><ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.mzv.cz/jnp/en/issues_and_press/factsheets/x2016_04_21_the_completion_of_translations_of_the.html |title=Short country name \"\u010cesko\"/\"Czechia\" to be entered in UN databases |date=21 April 2016 |website=Ministry of Foreign Affairs |access-date=31 December 2019 }}</ref> In September 2016, the British [[Permanent Committee on Geographical Names for British Official Use|Permanent Committee on Geographical Names]] (PCGN) recommended the use of ''Czechia'' and added it as the sole form of the country name to their list of country names.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/554812/Czechia_Information_Paper-Updated_September_2016.pdf |title = Czechia: New English-language country name for the Czech Republic |date=September 2016 |website=Permanent Committee on Geographical Names |access-date=31 December 2019 }}</ref> On 26 September 2016, the [[International Organization for Standardization]] included the short name ''Czechia'' in the official ISO 3166 country codes list.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:CZ |title = CZ: ISO 3166 codes for the representation of names of countries and their subdivisions |website=International Organization for Standardization |access-date=31 December 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/weather/2016/apr/14/czech-republic-czechia-new-name |title=Czech Republic officials say country would like to be called 'Czechia' instead |first=Oliver |last=Laughland |date=14 April 2016 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=31 December 2019}}</ref> The name ''Czechia'' and its respective translations are also included in the interinstitutional style guide of the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://publications.europa.eu/code/en/en-370100.htm |title = Interinstitutional style guide: Countries, Designations and abbreviations to use |website = [[Europa (web portal)|Europa.eu]] |access-date=2018-09-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://publications.europa.eu/code/en/en-000300.htm |title = News: Latest modifications |date=18 September 2018 |website=Europa |access-date=2018-09-21 }}</ref>\n\nMultinational technology companies that adopted the name ''Czechia'' include [[Google]]<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.idnes.cz/technet/software/czechia-google-mapy-maps-oficial-name-czech-republic-czechia.A170120_084107_tec-kratke-zpravy_pka |title = A je to \"ofici\u00e1ln\u00ed\". Mapy Google za\u010daly \u010cesku \u0159\u00edkat Czechia |trans-title = And it's \"official\". Google Maps calls \u010cesko Czechia |date=2017-01-20 |website=[[Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|iDNES]] |language=cs |access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref> and [[Apple Inc.|Apple]].<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/19/world/africa/swaziland-eswatini-name-change.html |title=Swaziland's King Wants His Country to Be Called eSwatini |last=Chan |first=Sewell |date=April 19, 2018 |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=31 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Other languages==\n{{refimprove section|date=October 2019}}\nThe equivalent of the Czech short form {{lang|cs|\u010cesko}} is in routine use by most other languages. In a few cases (for example [[Polish language|Polish]] {{lang|pl|Czechy}}, [[Croatian language|Croatian]] {{lang|sh|\u010ce\u0161ka}} and [[Serbian language|Serbian]] {{lang|sh|\u0427\u0435\u0448\u043a\u0430/\u010ce\u0161ka}}) this form had historically been used for Bohemia. Other languages adopted new short forms such as {{lang|ar|\u062a\u0634\u064a\u0643\u064a\u0627}} ''Tsh\u012bky\u0101'' in [[Arabic]].<!--Note that the example {{lang|zh|\u6377\u514b}} (''Ji\u00e9k\u00e8'' in [[Standard Mandarin|Mandarin]]) in [[Chinese language|Chinese]] does not make sense in this context because the exact same Chinese characters have been used to translate the Czech part of Czechoslovakia--> In most cases, the new form has more or less completely replaced the formal name for most usages. However, usage in Spanish and French remains mixed, with the forms {{lang|es|Chequia}} and {{lang|fr|Tch\u00e9quie}} occasionally being used alongside the longer formal names {{lang|es|Rep\u00fablica Checa}} and {{lang|fr|R\u00e9publique tch\u00e8que}}.\n\n===German===\nIn German, the term applicable to the Czech part of Czechoslovakia used to be {{lang|de|Tschechei}}, comparable to {{lang|de|Slowakei}} for [[Slovakia]]. However, the term began to have negative connotations in connection with the [[Nazis]], who used the term {{lang|de|Rest-Tschechei}} \"[[rump state|remaining]] Czechia\" when [[Munich Agreement|they annexed the border regions of western Czechoslovakia in 1938]]. Since the end of the Second World War, the term {{lang|de|Tschechien}} has been used instead, as suggested by the Czech Ministry of Foreign Affairs as well as German and Austrian linguists. {{lang|de|Tschechien}} is a term from the 19th century that was originally used for the Czech lands that were part of [[Austria-Hungary]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.czech-tourist.de/tschechei.htm |title=Zum Begriff \"Tschechei\": Problematik und Sprachgebrauch |trans-title=About the term \"Czech Republic\": Issues and use of language |website=Czech Tourist |language=de |accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref> The German [[Federal Foreign Office]] uses Tschechien in its official list of countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.auswaertiges-amt.de/DE/Aussenpolitik/Laender/Laenderinfos/01-Nodes_Uebersichtsseiten/TschechischeRepublik_node.html |title=Tschechien |website=[[Federal Foreign Office|Ausw\u00e4rtiges Amt]] |language=de |accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bohemian]]\n* [[Hyphen War]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|Czech Republic}}\n*{{in lang|cs}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191931/https://www.national-geographic.cz/detail.asp?id=952 \"Open letter to the Czech Olympic Foundation, Czech Sports Union, politicians, business people, media, etc.\"], ''National Geographic'', 2001.\n*{{in lang|en}} [http://www.radio.cz/en/article/53850 \"Looking for a name\"] by Daniela Lazarova, Radio Prague, 13 May 2004.\n*{{in lang|en}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20110807053615/http://historia.arch.p.lodz.pl/jw37/EUROPE/cesko1.htm \"\u010cesko versus Czechy? On the geographic name of the Czech Republic\"] by Leo\u0161 Jele\u010dek, paper presented at the 2nd Slovak-Czech-Polish Geographical Seminar, Bratislava, 1\u20135 September 1999.{{dead link |date=September 2017}}\n* {{in lang|en}} [http://www.radio.cz/en/section/letter/from-bohemia-to-czechia \"From Bohemia to Czechia\"] Ji\u0159\u00ed \u0160itler (12 July 2016) [[Radio Prague]]\n\n{{Europe topic|Name of}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Geographical naming disputes|Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Names of places in Europe]]\n[[Category:Country name etymology|Czech Republic]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCzech-language name:Fixed cite error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Name_of_the_Czech_Republic"}
