opulated places in Baranya County]]\n\n\n{{Baranya-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name          = Huszt\u00f3t\n| native_name            =\n| other_name             =\n| settlement_type        = Village\n| image_skyline          =\n| image_caption          =\n| image_flag             =\n| image_seal             =\n| nickname               =\n| motto                  =\n| image_map              =\n| map_caption            =\n| pushpin_map            =\n| pushpin_label_position =\n| pushpin_map_caption    =\n| coordinates            = {{coord|46|10|N|18|05|E|region:HU_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type       = Country\n| subdivision_name       = {{flag|Hungary}}\n| subdivision_type1      = [[Counties of Hungary|County]]\n| subdivision_name1      = [[Baranya (county)|Baranya]]\n| subdivision_type2      =\n| subdivision_name2      =\n| established_title      =\n| established_date       =\n| government_type        =\n| government_footnotes   =\n| leader_title           =\n| leader_name            =\n| unit_pref              = Imperial\n| area_footnotes         =\n| area_total_km2         =\n| area_land_km2          =\n| elevation_footnotes    =\n| elevation_m            =\n| elevation_ft           =\n| population_footnotes   =\n| population_total       =\n| population_as_of       =\n| population_density_km2 =\n| population_note        =\n| timezone               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset             = +1\n| timezone_DST           = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST         = +2\n| postal_code_type       =\n| postal_code            =\n| area_code              =\n| website                =\n| footnotes              =\n}}\n\n'''Huszt\u00f3t''' is a village in [[Baranya (county)|Baranya]] county, [[Hungary]].\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://portal.ksh.hu/pls/portal/cp.hnt_telep?NN=31431 Local statistics] {{in lang|hu}}\n\n{{Baranya}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Husztot}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Baranya County]]\n\n\n{{Baranya-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Huszt%C3%B3t"}
{"title_page": "Hurden", "text_new": "{{Infobox Swiss town\n| subject_name = Hurden\n| within_municipality = [[Freienbach]]\n| municipality_type = former\n| imagepath_coa\t= |pixel_coa =\n| image_photo = Hurden - Seedamm - Rapperswil Endingen - Frohberg IMG 5138.jpg\n| image_caption = [[Seedamm]] and Hurden, as seen from ''Frohberg'' hill in [[Kempraten]]-''Lenggis'', the [[Kapuzinerkloster Rapperswil|Capuchin monastery]] in [[Rapperswil]] to the left, [[Pf\u00e4ffikon, Schwyz|Pf\u00e4ffikon]] in the background\n| map = \n| languages = German\n| canton = Schwyz\n| iso-code-region = CH-SZ\n| district = [[H\u00f6fe (district)|H\u00f6fe]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|47|11.6|N|8|46.6|E|display=inline,title}}\n|lat_NS=N|long_EW=E\n| postal_code = 8640\n| municipality_code = 1322\n| area = 1.31\n| elevation = 408|elevation_description= \n| population = 271|populationof = December 2008  \n| website = www.freienbach.ch\n| mayor = |mayor_asof=|mayor_party=\n| mayor_title = |list_of_mayors\t= \n| places = \n| demonym = \n| neighboring_municipalities= [[Altendorf, Switzerland]], [[Pf\u00e4ffikon, Schwyz|Pf\u00e4ffikon]], [[Rapperswil]]\n| twintowns = \n|}}\n'''Hurden''' is a [[Municipalities of Switzerland|village]] in the municipality of [[Freienbach]] in the [[Cantons of Switzerland|canton]] of [[Schwyz (canton)|Schwyz]] in [[Switzerland]]. First mentioned in 1217, the name \"de Hurden\" was used for the peninsula and for the fish traps made of woven work, called \"H\u00fcrden\" or \"Hurden\", which were used by the locals.\n[[File:Holzbr\u00fccke - Hurden IMG 3850.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Holzbr\u00fccke Rapperswil-Hurden]] as seen from Hurden, Rapperswil to the left, [[Jona]] to the right]]\n[[File:Hurden - Obersee - Rapperswil IMG 3849.jpg|thumb|upright|Hurden and [[Obersee (Z\u00fcrichsee)|''Obersee'']] (upper Lake Z\u00fcrich) as seen from [[Holzbr\u00fccke Rapperswil-Hurden|''Holzbr\u00fccke'']] in [[Rapperswil]]]]\n[[File:Kapelle zu Ehren der heiligsten Dreieinigkeit in Hurden 2017-11-22 14-07-56.JPG|thumb|upright|''Kapelle zu Ehren der heiligsten Dreieinigkeit'' ([[Holy Trinity]] chapel) in Hurden]]\n[[File:Mittelholzer Hurden Seedamm 1929.jpg|thumb|upright|Hurden, [[Seedamm]] and [[Rapperswil]] on an [[aerial photography]] by [[Walter Mittelholzer]] (1929)]]\n\n== Geography ==\nThe village of Hurden is located on a [[peninsula]] protruding from the southern shore of [[Lake Z\u00fcrich]] at its narrowest point. The peninsula has its origin in the retreat of the [[Linth]] glacier at the end of the [[last glacial period]] when Lake Z\u00fcrich was formed. This retreat left a [[moraine]] across the valley now occupied by Lake Z\u00fcrich. The higher southern section of this moraine extends above the lake's water level and forms the peninsula, whilst the lower northern section forms a shallow section in the otherwise deep lake. Together these separate Lake Z\u00fcrich into two parts, the larger lower lake to the north-west, and the smaller upper lake ([[Obersee (Z\u00fcrichsee)|''Obersee'']]) to the east.\n\nThe artificial [[Seedamm]] uses a combination of artificial causeways and bridges to cross the shallow water between the tip of the peninsula to [[Rapperswil]] on the northern shore of the lake, and carries both road and rail links. To the west of the Seedamm, there is a wooden bridge for pedestrians (''[[Holzbr\u00fccke Rapperswil-Hurden]]''), which was built in 2001 as a reconstruction of the first bridge between eastern and western lakesides.<ref name=\"Seedamm wird saniert\">{{cite news | work = [[Tages-Anzeiger]] | date = March 9, 2010 | url = http://www.tagesanzeiger.ch/zuerich/region/Seedamm-wird-saniert/story/17119650 | title = Seedamm wird saniert | language = German |trans-title=Causeway is being renovated}}</ref> Since the construction of the [[Hurden ship canal]], across the base of the peninsula, the natural peninsula has been transformed into an artificial island. The ''Sternenbr\u00fccke'' bridge carries both road and railway across the ship canal.\n\nAt Hurden also the ''[[Frauenwinkel]]'' protected area is situated. Its name origins from a donation by the emperor [[Otto I]] in 965 AD to the pin ''Unserer lieben Frau'' (''Our Lady'') to the [[Einsiedeln Abbey]].<ref name=\"freienbach\">{{cite web|url=http://www.freienbach.ch/xml_1/internet/en/application/d820/d821/f828.cfm?highlight=Frauenwinkel|title=Frauenwinkel|publisher=Gemeinde Freienbach|author=|date=|accessdate=2014-11-07}}</ref>\n\n== Transport ==\nThe village is transited by the Rapperswil\u2013Pf\u00e4ffikon railway line and by a major road, both of which cross the [[Seedamm]]. [[Hurden railway station]], in the village, is served by [[Z\u00fcrich S-Bahn]] lines [[S5 (ZVV)|S5]] and [[S40 (ZVV)|S40]]. In 1943 southern Hurden was divided by the construction of the [[Hurden ship canal]], which connected the upper to the lower Lake Z\u00fcrich. Now the ships of the [[Z\u00fcrichsee-Schifffahrtsgesellschaft]] (ZSG) were able to pass from Lake Z\u00fcrich to the upper Lake Z\u00fcrich, and the peninsula actually was a real island which was cut off from the mainland. The ''Sternenbr\u00fccke'' bridge, across the Hurden ship canal, was renewed between March 15 and November 2010 to allow 40 ton trucks to cross the Seedamm.<ref name=\"Seedamm wird saniert\"/>\n\n== History ==\nArchaeological relicts have been found at the [[Rapperswil-Jona\u2013Technikum|''Technikum'' island settlement]],<ref name=\"palafittes-sg02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|title=Sites Switzerland: ''Rapperswil-Jona\u2013Technikum'' (CH-SG-02)|publisher=palafittes.org|author=|language=|date=|accessdate=2014-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007220441/http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|archive-date=2014-10-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the remains of a first [[Holzbr\u00fccke Rapperswil-Hurden|wooden bridge]] (1523 BC, reconstructed in 2001) to Hurden located on the [[Obersee (Z\u00fcrichsee)|''Obersee'']] lakeshore nearby the so-called ''[[Heilig H\u00fcsli]]'' at the northwestern part of the [[Seedamm]] area. The four neighbouring [[Prehistoric pile dwellings around Z\u00fcrichsee|Prehistoric settlements]], as well as the early lake crossings, are part of the [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]] ''[[Prehistoric pile dwellings around Z\u00fcrichsee|Prehistoric Pile dwellings around the Alps]]'',<ref name=\"palafittes-\u00fcbersicht\">{{cite web|url=http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|title=Prehistoric Pile Dwellings in Switzerland|publisher=Swiss Coordination Group UNESCO Palafittes (palafittes.org)|author=|language=|date=|accessdate=2014-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007220441/http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|archive-date=2014-10-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> including also the settlements [[Freienbach\u2013Hurden Rosshorn]]<ref name=\"palafittes-sz01\">{{cite web|url=http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|title=Sites Switzerland: ''Freienbach\u2013Hurden Rosshorn'' (CH-SZ-01)|publisher=palafittes.org|author=|language=|date=|accessdate=2014-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007220441/http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|archive-date=2014-10-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Freienbach\u2013Hurden Seefeld]].<ref name=\"palafittes-sz02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|title=Sites Switzerland: ''Freienbach\u2013Hurden Seefeld'' (CH-SZ-02)|publisher=palafittes.org|author=|language=|date=|accessdate=2014-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007220441/http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|archive-date=2014-10-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> Around 1523 BC, also the first lake crossings on [[Obersee (Z\u00fcrichsee)|''Obersee'']] between Rapperswil and Hurden were discovered in 2001, followed by several reconstructions at least until the late 2nd century AD when the [[Roman Empire]] built {{convert|6|m|ft|sp=us}} wide wooden bridge under Empire [[Marcus Aurelius]] (161-180).<ref>''Unterwasserarch\u00e4ologische Projekte Kanton St. Gallen''</ref><ref name=\"NZZ_20010121\">[[Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung]] (January 20/21, 2001): '' Die Br\u00fccke auf dem Grund des Z\u00fcrichsees]''</ref>\n\nHistorians mention a 10th-century ferry station assumably at the so-called ''[[Einsiedlerhaus]]'' in Rapperswil  \u2013 in 981 AD as well as the vineyard on the [[Lindenhof (Rapperswil)|Lindenhof hill]] \u2013 between [[Kempraten]] on lake shore, [[L\u00fctzelau]] and [[Ufenau]] island and assumably present Hurden, which allowed the pilgrims towards Einsiedeln to cross the lake before the [[Holzbr\u00fccke Rapperswil-Hurden|prehistoric bridge]] at the Seedamm isthmus was re-built.<ref name=\"kapuzinerkloster\">{{cite web|url=http://klosterrapperswil.ch/das-einsiedlerhaus-in-rapperswil-wechselt-den-besitzer/|title=Das Einsiedlerhaus in Rapperswil wechselt den Besitzer|publisher=[[Kapuzinerkloster Rapperswil]], published by Markus Turnherr, [[Rathaus Rapperswil#Stadtarchiv|Stadtarchivar]], in ''[[Obersee Nachrichten]]''|author=|language=German|date=|accessdate=2015-09-12}}</ref> By 1358, ferry services between Rapperswil and Hurden are mentioned. Between 1358 and 1360, [[Rudolf IV, Duke of Austria]], built a wooden bridge across the lake that has been used to 1878 \u2013 measuring approximately {{convert|1450|m|ft|sp=us}} in length and {{convert|4|m|ft|sp=us}} wide. A small wooden bridge from Ufenau island to Hurden is mentioned around 1430, so-called \u00abKilchweg in die Uffnow\u00bb, meaning ''chorchgoing to the [[Ufnau]] island''. During [[Old Z\u00fcrich War]] in 1443 the bridge was set on fire, and as a result of the Second [[Toggenburg War|Battle of Villmergen]] in 1712, Hurden was reigned by the Protestant cantons of Z\u00fcrich, Bern and Glarus.<ref name=\"hds-\">{{cite web|url=http://pfaeffikon.uch.ch/pf_hurd/FrameSet.htm|title=Die Geschichte von Hurden|publisher=pfaeffikon.uch.ch|author=|language=German|date=|accessdate=2014-12-07}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Helvetic Republic]], in 1798, Hurden became part of the new established ''Distrikt Rapperswil'' in the [[Canton of Linth]], and in 1803 it was part of the new established [[Pf\u00e4ffikon, Schwyz|Pf\u00e4ffikon]]. In 1873 the Swiss federal parliament approved the construction of the today's stone dam and bridge. Beginning in 1990, luxurious villas were widely built in Hurden, which in part on newly reclaimed area created for and with a private harbour.\n\nIn 2001 a new wooden footbridge was opened alongside the dam for the first {{convert|840|m|ft|sp=us}} meters of the crossing. It was built in quite the same place as the original bridge linking Rapperswil with the nearby bridge chapel (''[[Heilig H\u00fcsli]]'').\n\n== Cultural Heritage ==\nLocated on ''[[Obersee (Z\u00fcrichsee)|Obersee]]'' lakeshore in Hurden and situated at the ''[[Seedamm]]'' isthmus between the ''Z\u00fcrichsee'' and the ''Obersee'' lake area, the area was in close vicinity to the [[Holzbr\u00fccke Rapperswil-Hurden|prehistoric lake crossings]], neighbored by four Prehistoric pile dwelling settlements: [[Freienbach\u2013Hurden Rosshorn]],<ref name=\"palafittes-sz01\"/> [[Freienbach\u2013Hurden Seefeld]],<ref name=\"palafittes-sz02\"/> [[Seegubel]]<ref name=\"palafittes-sg01\">{{cite web|url=http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|title=Sites Switzerland: ''Rapperswil-Jona/Hombrechtikon\u2013Feldbach'' (CH-SG-01)|publisher=palafittes.org|author=|language=|date=|accessdate=2014-12-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007220441/http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|archive-date=2014-10-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Rapperswil-Jona\u2013Technikum]].<ref name=\"palafittes-sg02\"/> Because the lake has grown in size over time, the original piles are now around {{convert|4|m|ft|0}} to {{convert|7|m|ft|0}} under the water level of {{convert|406|m|ft|0}}.\n\nAs well as being part of the 56 Swiss sites of the UNESCO World Heritage Site ''Prehistoric pile dwellings around the Alps'', the settlements are also listed in the [[Swiss inventory of cultural property of national and regional significance]] as ''Class A'' objects of national importance.<ref name=\"kgs-sz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bevoelkerungsschutz.admin.ch/internet/bs/de/home/themen/kgs/kgs_inventar/a-objekte.parsys.00018.DownloadFile.tmp/sz2015.pdf |title=A-Objekte KGS-Inventar (Kanton Schwyz) |publisher=Schweizerische Eidgenossenschaft, Amt f\u00fcr Bev\u00f6lkerungsschutz |date=2015-01-01 |accessdate=2015-09-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617061303/http://www.bevoelkerungsschutz.admin.ch/internet/bs/de/home/themen/kgs/kgs_inventar/a-objekte.parsys.00018.DownloadFile.tmp/sz2015.pdf |archivedate=2015-06-17 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Prehistoric pile dwellings around the Alps]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Hurden}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.freienbach.ch/xml_1/internet/de/application/d2/d357/f360.cfm}} {{in lang|de}}\n* {{HDS|7441|Hurden}}\n\n{{Lake Zurich}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in the canton of Schwyz]]\n[[Category:Populated places on Lake Zurich]]\n[[Category:Freienbach]]\n[[Category:Cultural property of national significance in the canton of Schwyz]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Swiss town\n| subject_name = Hurden\n| within_municipality = [[Freienbach]]\n| municipality_type = former\n| imagepath_coa\t= |pixel_coa =\n| image_photo = Hurden - Seedamm - Rapperswil Endingen - Frohberg IMG 5138.jpg\n| image_caption = [[Seedamm]] and Hurden, as seen from ''Frohberg'' hill in [[Kempraten]]-''Lenggis'', the [[Kapuzinerkloster Rapperswil|Capuchin monastery]] in [[Rapperswil]] to the left, [[Pf\u00e4ffikon, Schwyz|Pf\u00e4ffikon]] in the background\n| map = \n| languages = German\n| canton = Schwyz\n| iso-code-region = CH-SZ\n| district = [[H\u00f6fe (district)|H\u00f6fe]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|47|11.6|N|8|46.6|E|display=inline,title}}\n|lat_NS=N|long_EW=E\n| postal_code = 8640\n| municipality_code = 1322\n| area = 1.31\n| elevation = 408|elevation_description= \n| population = 271|populationof = December 2008  \n| website = www.freienbach.ch\n| mayor = |mayor_asof=|mayor_party=\n| mayor_title = |list_of_mayors\t= \n| places = \n| demonym = \n| neighboring_municipalities= [[Altendorf, Switzerland]], [[Pf\u00e4ffikon, Schwyz|Pf\u00e4ffikon]], [[Rapperswil]]\n| twintowns = \n|}}\n'''Hurden''' is a [[Municipalities of Switzerland|village]] in the municipality of [[Freienbach]] in the [[Cantons of Switzerland|canton]] of [[Schwyz (canton)|Schwyz]] in [[Switzerland]]. First mentioned in 1217, the name \"de Hurden\" was used for the peninsula and for the fish traps made of woven work, called \"H\u00fcrden\" or \"Hurden\", which were used by the locals.\n[[File:Holzbr\u00fccke - Hurden IMG 3850.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Holzbr\u00fccke Rapperswil-Hurden]] as seen from Hurden, Rapperswil to the left, [[Jona]] to the right]]\n[[File:Hurden - Obersee - Rapperswil IMG 3849.jpg|thumb|upright|Hurden and [[Obersee (Z\u00fcrichsee)|''Obersee'']] (upper Lake Z\u00fcrich) as seen from [[Holzbr\u00fccke Rapperswil-Hurden|''Holzbr\u00fccke'']] in [[Rapperswil]]]]\n[[File:Kapelle zu Ehren der heiligsten Dreieinigkeit in Hurden 2017-11-22 14-07-56.JPG|thumb|upright|''Kapelle zu Ehren der heiligsten Dreieinigkeit'' ([[Holy Trinity]] chapel) in Hurden]]\n[[File:Mittelholzer Hurden Seedamm 1929.jpg|thumb|upright|Hurden, [[Seedamm]] and [[Rapperswil]] on an [[aerial photography]] by [[Walter Mittelholzer]] (1929)]]\n\n== Geography ==\nThe village of Hurden is located on a [[peninsula]] protruding from the southern shore of [[Lake Z\u00fcrich]] at its narrowest point. The peninsula has its origin in the retreat of the [[Linth]] glacier at the end of the [[last glacial period]] when Lake Z\u00fcrich was formed. This retreat left a [[moraine]] across the valley now occupied by Lake Z\u00fcrich. The higher southern section of this moraine extends above the lake's water level and forms the peninsula, whilst the lower northern section forms a shallow section in the otherwise deep lake. Together these separate Lake Z\u00fcrich into two parts, the larger lower lake to the north-west, and the smaller upper lake ([[Obersee (Z\u00fcrichsee)|''Obersee'']]) to the east.\n\nThe artificial [[Seedamm]] uses a combination of artificial causeways and bridges to cross the shallow water between the tip of the peninsula to [[Rapperswil]] on the northern shore of the lake, and carries both road and rail links. To the west of the Seedamm, there is a wooden bridge for pedestrians (''[[Holzbr\u00fccke Rapperswil-Hurden]]''), which was built in 2001 as a reconstruction of the first bridge between eastern and western lakesides.<ref name=\"Seedamm wird saniert\">{{cite news | work = [[Tages-Anzeiger]] | date = March 9, 2010 | url = http://www.tagesanzeiger.ch/zuerich/region/Seedamm-wird-saniert/story/17119650 | title = Seedamm wird saniert | language = German |trans-title=Causeway is being renovated}}</ref> Since the construction of the [[Hurden ship canal]], across the base of the peninsula, the natural peninsula has been transformed into an artificial island. The ''Sternenbr\u00fccke'' bridge carries both road and railway across the ship canal.\n\nAt Hurden also the ''[[Frauenwinkel]]'' protected area is situated. Its name origins from a donation by the emperor [[Otto I]] in 965 AD to the pin ''Unserer lieben Frau'' (''Our Lady'') to the [[Einsiedeln Abbey]].<ref name=\"freienbach\">{{cite web|url=http://www.freienbach.ch/xml_1/internet/en/application/d820/d821/f828.cfm?highlight=Frauenwinkel|title=Frauenwinkel|publisher=Gemeinde Freienbach|author=|date=|accessdate=2014-11-07}}</ref>\n\n== Transport ==\nThe village is transited by the Rapperswil\u2013Pf\u00e4ffikon railway line and by a major road, both of which cross the [[Seedamm]]. [[Hurden railway station]], in the village, is served by [[Z\u00fcrich S-Bahn]] lines [[S5 (ZVV)|S5]] and [[S40 (ZVV)|S40]]. In 1943 southern Hurden was divided by the construction of the [[Hurden ship canal]], which connected the upper to the lower Lake Z\u00fcrich. Now the ships of the [[Z\u00fcrichsee-Schifffahrtsgesellschaft]] (ZSG) were able to pass from Lake Z\u00fcrich to the upper Lake Z\u00fcrich, and the peninsula actually was a real island which was cut off from the mainland. The ''Sternenbr\u00fccke'' bridge, across the Hurden ship canal, was renewed between March 15 and November 2010 to allow 40 ton trucks to cross the Seedamm.<ref name=\"Seedamm wird saniert\"/>\n\n== History ==\nArchaeological relicts have been found at the [[Rapperswil-Jona\u2013Technikum|''Technikum'' island settlement]],<ref name=\"palafittes-sg02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|title=Sites Switzerland: ''Rapperswil-Jona\u2013Technikum'' (CH-SG-02)|publisher=palafittes.org|author=|language=|date=|accessdate=2014-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007220441/http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|archive-date=2014-10-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the remains of a first [[Holzbr\u00fccke Rapperswil-Hurden|wooden bridge]] (1523 BC, reconstructed in 2001) to Hurden located on the [[Obersee (Z\u00fcrichsee)|''Obersee'']] lakeshore nearby the so-called ''[[Heilig H\u00fcsli]]'' at the northwestern part of the [[Seedamm]] area. The four neighbouring [[Prehistoric pile dwellings around Z\u00fcrichsee|Prehistoric settlements]], as well as the early lake crossings, are part of the [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]] ''[[Prehistoric pile dwellings around Z\u00fcrichsee|Prehistoric Pile dwellings around the Alps]]'',<ref name=\"palafittes-\u00fcbersicht\">{{cite web|url=http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|title=Prehistoric Pile Dwellings in Switzerland|publisher=Swiss Coordination Group UNESCO Palafittes (palafittes.org)|author=|language=|date=|accessdate=2014-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007220441/http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|archive-date=2014-10-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> including also the settlements [[Freienbach\u2013Hurden Rosshorn]]<ref name=\"palafittes-sz01\">{{cite web|url=http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|title=Sites Switzerland: ''Freienbach\u2013Hurden Rosshorn'' (CH-SZ-01)|publisher=palafittes.org|author=|language=|date=|accessdate=2014-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007220441/http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|archive-date=2014-10-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Freienbach\u2013Hurden Seefeld]].<ref name=\"palafittes-sz02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|title=Sites Switzerland: ''Freienbach\u2013Hurden Seefeld'' (CH-SZ-02)|publisher=palafittes.org|author=|language=|date=|accessdate=2014-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007220441/http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|archive-date=2014-10-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> Around 1523 BC, also the first lake crossings on [[Obersee (Z\u00fcrichsee)|''Obersee'']] between Rapperswil and Hurden were discovered in 2001, followed by several reconstructions at least until the late 2nd century AD when the [[Roman Empire]] built {{convert|6|m|ft|sp=us}} wide wooden bridge under Empire [[Marcus Aurelius]] (161-180).<ref>''Unterwasserarch\u00e4ologische Projekte Kanton St. Gallen''</ref><ref name=\"NZZ_20010121\">[[Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung]] (January 20/21, 2001): '' Die Br\u00fccke auf dem Grund des Z\u00fcrichsees]''</ref>\n\nHistorians mention a 10th-century ferry station assumably at the so-called ''[[Einsiedlerhaus]]'' in Rapperswil  \u2013 in 981 AD as well as the vineyard on the [[Lindenhof (Rapperswil)|Lindenhof hill]] \u2013 between [[Kempraten]] on lake shore, [[L\u00fctzelau]] and [[Ufenau]] island and assumably present Hurden, which allowed the pilgrims towards Einsiedeln to cross the lake before the [[Holzbr\u00fccke Rapperswil-Hurden|prehistoric bridge]] at the Seedamm isthmus was re-built.<ref name=\"kapuzinerkloster\">{{cite web|url=http://klosterrapperswil.ch/das-einsiedlerhaus-in-rapperswil-wechselt-den-besitzer/|title=Das Einsiedlerhaus in Rapperswil wechselt den Besitzer|publisher=[[Kapuzinerkloster Rapperswil]], published by Markus Turnherr, [[Rathaus Rapperswil#Stadtarchiv|Stadtarchivar]], in ''[[Obersee Nachrichten]]''|author=|language=German|date=|accessdate=2015-09-12}}</ref> By 1358, ferry services between Rapperswil and Hurden are mentioned. Between 1358 and 1360, [[Rudolf IV, Duke of Austria]], built a wooden bridge across the lake that has been used to 1878 \u2013 measuring approximately {{convert|1450|m|ft|sp=us}} in length and {{convert|4|m|ft|sp=us}} wide. A small wooden bridge from Ufenau island to Hurden is mentioned around 1430, so-called \u00abKilchweg in die Uffnow\u00bb, meaning ''chorchgoing to the [[Ufnau]] island''. During [[Old Z\u00fcrich War]] in 1443 the bridge was set on fire, and as a result of the Second [[Toggenburg War|Battle of Villmergen]] in 1712, Hurden was reigned by the Protestant cantons of Z\u00fcrich, Bern and Glarus.<ref name=\"hds-\">{{cite web|url=http://pfaeffikon.uch.ch/pf_hurd/FrameSet.htm|title=Die Geschichte von Hurden|publisher=pfaeffikon.uch.ch|author=|language=German|date=|accessdate=2014-12-07}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Helvetic Republic]], in 1798, Hurden became part of the new established ''Distrikt Rapperswil'' in the [[Canton of Linth]], and in 1803 it was part of the new established [[Pf\u00e4ffikon, Schwyz|Pf\u00e4ffikon]]. In 1873 the Swiss federal parliament approved the construction of the today's stone dam and bridge. Beginning in 1990, luxurious villas were widely built in Hurden, which in part on newly reclaimed area created for and with a private harbour.\n\nIn 2001 a new wooden footbridge was opened alongside the dam for the first {{convert|840|m|ft|sp=us}} meters of the crossing. It was built in quite the same place as the original bridge linking Rapperswil with the nearby bridge chapel (''[[Heilig H\u00fcsli]]'').\n\n== Cultural Heritage ==\nLocated on ''[[Obersee (Z\u00fcrichsee)|Obersee]]'' lakeshore in Hurden and situated at the ''[[Seedamm]]'' isthmus between the ''Z\u00fcrichsee'' and the ''Obersee'' lake area, the area was in close vicinity to the [[Holzbr\u00fccke Rapperswil-Hurden|prehistoric lake crossings]], neighbored by four Prehistoric pile dwelling settlements: [[Freienbach\u2013Hurden Rosshorn]],<ref name=\"palafittes-sz01\"/> [[Freienbach\u2013Hurden Seefeld]],<ref name=\"palafittes-sz02\"/> [[Seegubel]]<ref name=\"palafittes-sg01\">{{cite web|url=http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|title=Sites Switzerland: ''Rapperswil-Jona/Hombrechtikon\u2013Feldbach'' (CH-SG-01)|publisher=palafittes.org|author=|language=|date=|accessdate=2014-12-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007220441/http://www.palafittes.org/en/unesco-world-heritage/sites-switzerland/index.html|archive-date=2014-10-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Rapperswil-Jona\u2013Technikum]].<ref name=\"palafittes-sg02\"/> Because the lake has grown in size over time, the original piles are now around {{convert|4|m|ft|0}} to {{convert|7|m|ft|0}} under the water level of {{convert|406|m|ft|0}}.\n\nAs well as being part of the 56 Swiss sites of the UNESCO World Heritage Site ''Prehistoric pile dwellings around the Alps'', the settlements are also listed in the [[Swiss inventory of cultural property of national and regional significance]] as ''Class A'' objects of national importance.<ref name=\"kgs-sz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bevoelkerungsschutz.admin.ch/internet/bs/de/home/themen/kgs/kgs_inventar/a-objekte.parsys.00018.DownloadFile.tmp/sz2015.pdf |title=A-Objekte KGS-Inventar (Kanton Schwyz) |publisher=Schweizerische Eidgenossenschaft, Amt f\u00fcr Bev\u00f6lkerungsschutz |date=2015-01-01 |accessdate=2015-09-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617061303/http://www.bevoelkerungsschutz.admin.ch/internet/bs/de/home/themen/kgs/kgs_inventar/a-objekte.parsys.00018.DownloadFile.tmp/sz2015.pdf |archivedate=2015-06-17 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Prehistoric pile dwellings around the Alps]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Hurden}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.freienbach.ch/xml_1/internet/de/application/d2/d357/f360.cfm}} {{in lang|de}}\n* {{HDS|7441|Hurden}}\n\n{{Lake Zurich}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in the canton of Schwyz]]\n[[Category:Populated places on Lake Zurich]]\n[[Category:Freienbach]]\n[[Category:Cultural property of national significance in the canton of Schwyz]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurden"}
